{"title_page": "Koh-i-Noor", "text_new": "{{Redirect|Kohinoor}}\n{{short description|One of the largest cut diamonds in the world, now part of the British Crown Jewels}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2011}}\n{{Infobox gem\n| name    = Koh-i-Noor\n| image   = Koh-i-Noor old version copy.jpg\n| image2  = Koh-i-Noor new version copy.jpg\n| caption = Glass replicas of the diamond before (upside down) and after it was re-cut in 1852\n| weight  = {{convert|105.602|carat|g}}{{efn|name=\"weight\"|Weights from {{frac|82|3|4}} to {{frac|122|3|4}} carats have been erroneously published since the 19th century.<ref name=\"israel\">Israel, p. 176.</ref> Until 1992, the official weight of the Koh-i-Noor was 108.93 metric carats,<ref>Balfour, p. 184.</ref> but this figure has been revised to 105.602 metric carats,<ref name=\"rose31\"/> or {{frac|102|13|16}} old English carats.<ref name=\"israel\"/>}}\n| dimensions = {{convert|3.6|cm|in|abbr=on}} long<br/>{{convert|3.2|cm|in|abbr=on}} wide<br/>{{convert|1.3|cm|in|1|abbr=on}} deep\n| colour  = D (colourless)<ref name=\"sucher126\">Sucher and Carriere, p. 126.</ref>\n| diamond_type = IIa<ref name=\"sucher126\"/>\n| cut = Oval brilliant\n| facets = 66<ref name=\"smith\">Smith, p. 77.</ref>\n| mine = [[Kollur Mine]]\n|country = [[India]]\n| cutter = Levie Benjamin Voorzanger\n| owner = Queen [[Elizabeth&nbsp;II]] in right of [[the Crown]]<ref>{{Cite Hansard |jurisdiction=United Kingdom |house=House of Commons |title=Crown Jewels |url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/written_answers/1992/jul/16/crown-jewels#column_944w |date=16 July 1992 |volume=211 |column=944W }}</ref>\n| value = Not insured<ref>{{Cite Hansard |jurisdiction=United Kingdom |house=House of Commons |title=Royal Residences |url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/written_answers/2003/jun/19/royal-residences#S6CV0407P0_20030619_CWA_85 |date=19 June 2003 |column=353W |volume=407 }}</ref>\n}}\nThe '''Koh-i-Noor''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02cc|k|\u0259\u028a|\u026a|\u02c8|n|\u028a\u0259r}}; {{lit}} \"Mountain of light\"),<ref name=\"EB2008\">{{cite encyclopedia |title=Koh-i-Noor|encyclopedia=Britannica Concise Encyclopedia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ea-bAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA1046 |date=2008 |publisher=[[Encyclopaedia Britannica]] |isbn=9781593394929 |page=1046 |language=English|quote=The Koh-i-noor (Hindi for \"mountain of light\") was acquired by the British in 1849 and became part of the Crown Jewels of Queen Victoria.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.collinsdictionary.com/dictionary/english/koh-i-noor|title=Definition of 'Koh-i-noor'|accessdate=26 November 2017|author=Collins English Dictionary|publisher=HarperCollins}}</ref> also spelt '''Kohinoor''' and '''Koh-i-Nur''', is one of the [[List of diamonds|largest cut diamonds]] in the world, weighing {{convert|105.6|carat|g}}.{{efn|name=\"weight\"}} It is part of the [[British Crown Jewels]].\n\nProbably mined in [[Kollur Mine]], India, during the period of the [[Delhi Sultanate]], there is no record of its original weight \u2013 but the earliest well-attested weight is 186 old carats (191 metric carats or 38.2&nbsp;g). The diamond was part of the [[Mughal emperors|Mughal]] [[Peacock Throne]]. It changed hands between various factions in south and west Asia, until being ceded to [[Queen Victoria]] after the [[Second Anglo-Sikh War|British annexation]] of the [[Punjab Province (British India)|Punjab]] in 1849.\n\nOriginally, the stone was of a similar cut to other [[Mughal Empire|Mughal-era]] diamonds, like the [[Darya-i-Noor]], which are now in the [[Iranian Crown Jewels]]. In 1851, it went on display at the [[Great Exhibition]] in London, but the lacklustre cut failed to impress viewers. [[Albert, Prince Consort|Prince Albert]], husband of Queen Victoria, ordered it to be re-cut as an oval brilliant by [[Coster Diamonds]]. By modern standards, the culet (point at the bottom of a gemstone) is unusually broad, giving the impression of a black hole when the stone is viewed head-on; it is nevertheless regarded by gemologists as \"full of life\".<ref>Howie, p. 293.</ref>\n\nBecause its history involves a great deal of fighting between men, the Koh-i-Noor acquired a reputation within the [[British royal family]] for bringing bad luck to any man who wears it.<!--cited end of paragraph--> Since arriving in the UK, it has only been worn by female members of the family.<ref>Mears, et al., p. 27.</ref> Victoria wore the stone in a brooch and a circlet. After she died in 1901, it was set in the [[Crown of Queen Alexandra]], wife of [[Edward VII]]. It was transferred to the [[Crown of Queen Mary]] in 1911, and finally to the [[Crown of Queen Elizabeth The Queen Mother|Crown of Queen Elizabeth]] (later known at the Queen Mother) in 1937 for her coronation as Queen consort.\n\nToday, the diamond is on public display in the [[Jewel House]] at the [[Tower of London]], where it is seen by millions of visitors each year. The governments of India, Pakistan, Iran, and Afghanistan have all claimed rightful ownership of the Koh-i-Noor and demanded its return ever since India gained independence from the UK in 1947. The British government insists the gem was obtained legally under the terms of the [[Treaty of Lahore#Text of the 1849 Last Treaty of Lahore|Last Treaty of Lahore]] and has rejected the claims.<!-- all cited within article body -->\n\n== History ==\n=== Origin ===\nThe diamond may have been mined from [[Kollur Mine]],<ref>Fanthorpe, p. 202.</ref><ref>Mears (1988), p. 100.</ref> a series of {{convert|4|m|ft|adj=on}} deep [[Gravel pit|gravel-clay pits]] on the banks of [[Krishna River]] in the [[Golconda Sultanate|Golconda]] (present-day <!--It is in Andhra Pradesh not Telangana-->[[Andhra Pradesh]]<!--It is not in Telangana-->), [[India]].<ref>Kurien, p. 112.</ref> It is impossible to know exactly when or where it was found, and many unverifiable theories exist as to its original owner.<ref name=\"rose32\">Rose, p. 32.</ref>\n\n=== Early history ===\n[[Babur]], the [[Turco-Mongol]] founder of the [[Mughal Empire]], wrote about a \"famous\" diamond that weighed just over 187 old carats \u2013&nbsp;approximately the size of the 186-carat Koh-i-Noor.<ref>Streeter, pp. 116\u2013117, 130.</ref> Some historians think Babur's diamond is the earliest reliable reference to the Koh-i-Noor.<ref>Lafont, p. 48.</ref> According to his diary, it was acquired by [[Alauddin Khalji]], second ruler of the [[Khalji dynasty]] of the [[Delhi Sultanate]], when he [[Alauddin Khalji#Marwar and southern campaigns, 1307\u20131313|invaded the kingdoms of southern India]] at the beginning of the 14th&nbsp;century and was probably in the possession of [[Kakatiya dynasty]].<ref>{{cite book |title=India Before Europe |last1=Asher |first1=Catherine B. |last2=Talbot |first2=Cynthia |date=2006 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-0-52180-904-7 |page=40 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZvaGuaJIJgoC&pg=PA40# |accessdate=20 February 2019 |language=en}}</ref> It later passed to succeeding dynasties of the Sultanate, and Babur received the diamond in 1526 as a tribute for his conquest of [[Delhi]] and [[Agra]] at the [[Battle of Panipat (1526)|Battle of Panipat]].<ref name=\"rose32\"/>\n\n[[Shah Jahan]], the fifth Mughal emperor, had the stone placed into his ornate [[Peacock Throne]]. In 1658, his son and successor, [[Aurangzeb]], confined the ailing emperor to [[Agra Fort]]. While in the possession of Aurangzeb, it was allegedly cut by Hortenso Borgia, a Venetian [[lapidary]], reducing the weight of the large stone to {{convert|186|carat|g}}.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article96503185 |title=Fascinating history of world's best diamonds|newspaper=[[The Northern Star]] |location=Lismore, New South Wales |date=30 May 1953 | author=Leela Kohli|accessdate=31 August 2013 |page=6 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> For this carelessness, Borgia was reprimanded and fined 10,000 [[rupee]]s.<ref>Younghusband and Davenport, pp. 53\u201357.</ref> According to recent research, the story of Borgia cutting the diamond is not correct, and most probably mixed up with the [[Orlov (diamond)|Orlov]], part of [[Catherine the Great]]'s imperial Russian sceptre in the Kremlin.<ref name=\"bbc.com\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-india-38218308|title=Koh-i-Noor: Six myths about a priceless diamond|work=BBC News|date=9 December 2016|accessdate=30 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Maharaja Ranjit singh's treasure.jpg|thumb|upright|One of Ranjit Singh's favourite horses with the head of his stables. His jewels are shown, to scale, including the Koh-i-Noor (top centre).<ref>Eden, p. 14.</ref>]]\nFollowing the 1739 invasion of Delhi by [[Nadir Shah]], the [[Afsharid dynasty|Afsharid Shah of Persia]], the treasury of the Mughal Empire was looted by his army in an organised and thorough acquisition of the Mughal nobility's wealth.<ref name=\"davenport\"/> Along with millions of [[rupee]]s and an assortment of historic jewels, the Shah also carried away the Koh-i-Noor.<ref name=\"siebenhuner\">Kim Siebenh\u00fcner in Hofmeester and Grewe, pp. 27\u201328.</ref> He exclaimed ''Koh-i-Noor!'', Persian for \"Mountain of Light\", when he obtained the famous stone.<ref>Argenzio, p. 42.</ref> One of his consorts said, \"If a strong man were to throw four stones \u2013 one north, one south, one east, one west, and a fifth stone up into the air \u2013 and if the space between them were to be filled with gold, all would not equal the value of the Koh-i-Noor\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2016/feb/16/koh-i-noor-diamond-britain-illegally-india-pakistan-afghanistan-history-tower|title=The Koh-i-Noor diamond is in Britain illegally. But it should still stay there|author=Anita Anand|work=The Guardian|date=16 February 2016|accessdate=8 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nAfter Nadir Shah was killed and [[Division of the Afsharid Empire|his empire collapsed]] in 1747, the Koh-i-Noor fell to his grandson, who in 1751 gave it to [[Ahmad Shah Durrani]], founder of the [[Afghan Empire]], in return for his support.<ref name=\"siebenhuner\"/> One of Ahmed's descendants, [[Shuja Shah Durrani]], wore a bracelet containing the Koh-i-Noor on the occasion of [[Mountstuart Elphinstone]]'s visit to [[Peshawar]] in 1808.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Asiatic Journal and Monthly Register for British India and its Dependencies|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wjk9AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA177|volume=27|year=1838|publisher=W. H. Allen & Co.|page=177}}</ref> A year later, Shuja formed an alliance with the United Kingdom to help defend against a possible invasion of Afghanistan by Russia.<ref>{{cite book|author=William Dalrymple|title=Return of a King: The Battle for Afghanistan|isbn=978-1-408-8183-05 |publisher=Bloomsbury|year=2012|page=5}}</ref> He was quickly overthrown, but fled with the diamond to [[Lahore]], where [[Ranjit Singh]], founder of the [[Sikh Empire]], in return for his hospitality, insisted upon the gem being given to him, and he took possession of it in 1813.<ref name=\"davenport\">Davenport, pp. 57\u201359.</ref>\n\n=== In Ranjit Singh's possession ===\n\nRanjit Singh had the diamond examined by jewelers of Lahore for two days to ensure that Shuja had not tricked him. After the jewelers confirmed its genuineness, he donated 125,000 rupees to Shuja. Ranjit Singh then asked the principal jewelers of Amritsar to estimate the diamond's value; the jewelers declared that the value of the diamond was \"far beyond all computation\".{{sfn|Dalrymple|Anand|2017|p=83}} Ranjit Singh then fixed the diamond in the front of his turban, and paraded on an elephant to enable his subjects to see the diamond.{{sfn|Dalrymple|Anand|2017|pp=83-84}} He used to wear it as an armlet during major festivals such as [[Diwali]] and [[Dusserah]], and took it with him during travel. He would exhibit it to prominent visitors, especially British officers.{{sfn|Dalrymple|Anand|2017|p=84}}\n\nOne day, Ranjit Singh asked the diamond's former owners - Shuja and his wife Wafa Begum - to estimate its value. Wafa Begum replied that if a strong man threw a stone in four cardinal directions and vertically, Koh-i-Noor would be worth more than the gold and precious stones filled in the space. Ranjit Singh grew paranoid about the Koh-i-Noor being stolen, because in the past, another valuable jewel had been stolen from him while he was intoxicated. He kept the diamond within a high-security facility at the [[Gobindgarh Fort]] when it was not in use. When the diamond was to be transported, it was placed in a [[pannier]] on a guarded camel; 39 other camels with identical panniers were included in the convoy; the diamond was always placed on the first camel immediately behind the guards, but great secrecy was maintained regarding which camel carried it.{{sfn|Dalrymple|Anand|2017|p=84}} Only Ranjit Singh's treasurer Misr Beli Ram knew which camel carried the diamond.{{sfn|Dalrymple|Anand|2017|p=106}}\n\nIn June 1839, Ranjit Singh suffered his third [[stroke]], and it became apparent that he would die soon. On his deathbed, he started giving away his valuable possessions to religious charities, and appointed his eldest son [[Kharak Singh]] as his successor. A day before his death, on 26 June 1839, a major argument broke out between his courtiers regarding the fate of Koh-i-Noor.{{sfn|Dalrymple|Anand|2017|p=91}} Ranjit Singh himself was too weak to speak, and communicated using gestures. Bhai Gobind Ram, the head [[Brahmin]] of Ranjit Singh, insisted that the king had willed Koh-i-Noor and other jewels to the [[Jagannath Temple, Puri|Jagannath Temple]] in [[Puri]]: the king apparently supported this claim through gestures, as recorded in his court chronicle ''Umdat ul-Tawarikh''.{{sfn|Dalrymple|Anand|2017|pp=91-92}} However, treasurer Beli Ram insisted that it was a state property rather than Ranjit Singh's personal property, and therefore, should be handed over to Kharak Singh.{{sfn|Dalrymple|Anand|2017|p=92}}\n\nAfter Ranjit Singh's death, Beli Ram refused to send the diamond to the temple, and hid it in his vaults.{{sfn|Dalrymple|Anand|2017|p=107}} Meanwhile, Kharak Singh and prime minister [[Dhian Singh]] also issued orders stating that the diamond should not be taken out of Lahore.{{sfn|Dalrymple|Anand|2017|p=108}}\n\n=== In Gulab Singh's possession ===\nOn 8 October 1839 the new emperor Kharak Singh, was overthrown in a coup by his prime minister Dhian Singh. The prime minister's brother [[Gulab Singh]], [[Raja]] of [[Jammu]], came into possession of the Koh-i-Noor.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.pt/books?id=7dymBAAAQBAJ&pg=PT121&lpg=PT121&dq=koh+i+noor+dogra&source=bl&ots=xGtrOZwhsL&sig=ACfU3U2uSFXCyDt560eRW3WZ1olxzCSo0Q&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=koh%20i%20noor%20dogra&f=false|title=The Koh-i-noor Diamond|last=Amini|first=Iradj|date=2013-06-01|publisher=Roli Books Private Limited|isbn=978-93-5194-035-7}}</ref> Kharak Singh later died in prison, soon followed by the mysterious death of his son and successor [[Nau Nihal Singh]] on 5 November 1840. Gulab Singh held onto the stone until January 1841, when he presented it to emperor [[Sher Singh]] in order to win his favour,<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.pt/books?id=P4bNDUFhI9IC&pg=PA166&lpg=PA166&dq=gulab+singh+koh+i+noor&source=bl&ots=6CRR_w0gk7&sig=ACfU3U1bjyFKE8gZoefM145d17g0hrm9Fw&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=gulab%20singh%20koh%20i%20noor&f=false|title=History of Koh-i-Noor, Darya-i-Noor, and Taimur's Ruby|date=1985|publisher=Atlantic Publishers & Distri}}</ref> after his brother Dhian Singh negotiated a ceasefire between Sher Singh and the overthrown empress [[Chand Kaur]]. Gulab Singh had attempted to defend the widowed empress at her fort in Lahore, during two days of conflict and shelling by Sher Singh and his troops.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.pt/books?id=HBOMDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA177&lpg=PA177&dq=chand+kaur+gulab+singh+fort&source=bl&ots=vc28pFQqj6&sig=ACfU3U0kDzDxjZiEA8fveSYl2BFohl6SKg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjAtdWx8bfmAhVGcBQKHTowB50Q6AEwEXoECAsQAQ#v=onepage&q=chand%20kaur%20gulab%20singh%20fort&f=false|title=Emperor of the Five Rivers: The Life and Times of Maharajah Ranjit Singh|last=Sheikh|first=Mohamed|date=2017-03-17|publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing|isbn=978-1-78673-095-4}}</ref> Despite handing over the Koh-i-noor, Gulab Singh as a result of the ceasefire returned safely to Jammu with a wealth of gold and other jewels taken from the treasury.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.pt/books?id=OzZzFm4pLWQC&pg=PA185&lpg=PA185&dq=chand+kaur+jammu&source=bl&ots=-AwTWgGwdA&sig=ACfU3U1YrV8iDbkBiqS3YCOK6iRWNyDxbg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj63syz8rfmAhWGA2MBHbxsDAA4ChDoATAGegQIBhAB#v=onepage&q=chand%20kaur%20jammu&f=false|title=Advance Study in the History of Modern India (Volume-2: 1803-1920)|last=Chhabra|first=G. S.|date=2005|publisher=Lotus Press|isbn=978-81-89093-07-5}}</ref>\n\n==== Worn by child emperor Duleep Singh ====\nOn 15 September 1843, both Sher Singh and prime minister Dhian Singh were assassinated in a coup led by Ajit Singh Sandhawalia. However, the next day in a counter coup led by Dhian's son Hira Singh the assassins were killed. Aged 24, Hira Singh succeeded his father as prime minister, and installed the five year old infant Duleep Singh as emperor. The Koh-i-noor was now fastened to the arm of the child emperor in court at Lahore. Duleep Singh and his mother empress [[Jind Kaur]], had till then resided in Jammu, the kingdom governed by Gulab Singh.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.pt/books?id=EoJoDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA115&lpg=PA115&dq=Koh-i-Noor+sher+singh&source=bl&ots=eMkin6tPB-&sig=ACfU3U3x6foG-i11WhDLs7oa4TD_2zpK7Q&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjikrjop7bmAhWIkxQKHRovBN4Q6AEwGHoECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=Koh-i-Noor%20sher%20singh&f=false|title=Kohinoor: The Story of the World\u00d5s Most Infamous Diamond|last=Dalrymple|first=William|last2=Anand|first2=Anita|date=2016|publisher=Juggernaut Books|isbn=978-93-86228-08-6}}</ref>\n\nFollowing his nephew Prime Minister Hira Singh's assassination on 27 March 1844, and the subsequent outbreak of the [[First Anglo-Sikh War]], Gulab Singh himself led the Sikh empire as its prime minister, and despite defeat in the war, he became the first [[Maharaja]] of [[Jammu and Kashmir (princely state)|Jammu and Kashmir]] on 16 March 1846, under the [[Treaty of Amritsar (1846)|Treaty of Amritsar]].\n\n=== Acquisition by Queen Victoria ===\nOn 29 March 1849, following the conclusion of the [[Second Anglo-Sikh War]], the Kingdom of [[Punjab Province (British India)|Punjab]] was formally annexed to [[Company rule in India|Company rule]], and the [[Treaty of Lahore#Text of the 1849 Last Treaty of Lahore|Last Treaty of Lahore]] was signed, officially ceding the Koh-i-Noor to [[Queen Victoria]] and the Maharaja's other assets to the company. Article III of the treaty read: \"The gem called the Koh-i-Noor, which was taken from Shah Sooja-ool-moolk by Maharajah Ranjeet Singh, shall be surrendered by the Maharajah of Lahore to the Queen of England (''sic'')\".<ref>Login, p. 126.</ref>\n\nThe lead signatory of the treaty for the eleven-year-old Maharaja Duleep Singh was his commander-in-chief [[Tej Singh]], a loyalist of Maharaja [[Gulab Singh]] who had previously been in possession of the Koh-i-noor and gained [[Kashmir]] from the Sikh empire, via treaty with Britain, following the [[First Anglo-Sikh War]].\n\nThe [[Governor-General of India|Governor-General]] in charge of the ratification of this treaty was the [[James Broun-Ramsay, 1st Marquess of Dalhousie|Marquess of Dalhousie]]. The manner of his aiding in the transfer of the diamond was criticized even by some of his contemporaries in Britain. Although some thought it should have been presented as a gift to Queen Victoria by the East India Company, it is clear that Dalhousie believed the stone was a spoil of war, and treated it accordingly, ensuring that it was officially surrendered to her by [[Duleep Singh]], the youngest son of Ranjit Singh.<ref>Broun-Ramsay, pp. 87\u201388</ref> The presentation of the Koh-i-Noor by the East India Company to the queen was the latest in a long history of transfers of the diamond as a coveted spoil of war.<ref name=\"keay\">Keay, pp. 156\u2013158</ref> Duleep Singh had been placed in the guardianship of Dr John Login, a surgeon in the British Army serving in the [[Presidency of Bengal]]. Duleep Singh would move to England in 1854.\n\n==== Journey to the United Kingdom ====\n[[File:Croquis du Koh-i-Noor d'apr\u00e8s Tavernier.jpg|thumb|Diagram of the pre-1852 cut.<ref>Valentine Ball in Jean Baptiste Tavernier, ''Travels in India'', 1889, Macmillan, vol. II, Appendix, plate VI.</ref><br /><br />'''Fig I'''. Shaded area is the base.<br />'''Fig II'''. A: flaw; B and C: notches cut to hold stone in a setting; D: flaw created by fracture at E; F: fracture created by a blow; G: unpolished cleavage plane; H: basal cleavage plane.<br />'''Fig III'''. Opposite side, showing facets and peak of the \"Mountain of Light\"]]\nIn due course, the Governor-General received the Koh-i-Noor from Dr Login, who had been appointed Governor of the Citadel, on 6 April 1848 under a receipt dated 7 December 1849, in the presence of members of the Board of Administration for the affairs of the Punjab: [[Henry Montgomery Lawrence|Sir Henry Lawrence]] (President), C. G. Mansel, [[John Lawrence, 1st Baron Lawrence|John Lawrence]] and Sir Henry Elliot (Secretary to the Government of India).\n\nLegend in the Lawrence family has it that before the voyage, John Lawrence left the jewel in his waistcoat pocket when it was sent to be laundered, and was most grateful when it was returned promptly by the [[valet]] who found it.<ref name=\"Birdwood1946\">{{cite book|author=William Riddell Birdwood|title=In My Time: Recollections and Anecdotes|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9GwgAAAAMAAJ|year=1946|publisher=Skeffington & Son|page=85}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 February 1850, the jewel was sealed in a small iron safe inside a red dispatch box, both sealed with red tape and a wax seal and kept in a chest at Bombay Treasury awaiting a steamer ship from China. It was then sent to England for presentation to Queen Victoria in the care of Captain J. Ramsay and Brevet Lt. Col F. Mackeson under tight security arrangements, one of which was the placement of the dispatch box in a larger iron safe. They departed from Bombay on 6 April on board HMS ''Medea'', captained by Captain Lockyer.\n\nThe ship had a difficult voyage: an outbreak of [[cholera]] on board when the ship was in [[Mauritius]] had the locals demanding its departure, and they asked their governor to open fire on the vessel and destroy it if there was no response. Shortly afterwards, the vessel was hit by a severe gale that blew for some 12 hours.\n\nOn arrival in Britain on 29 June, the passengers and mail were unloaded in [[Plymouth]], but the Koh-i-Noor stayed on board until the ship reached [[Spithead]], near [[Portsmouth]], on 1 July. The next morning, Ramsay and Mackeson, in the company of Mr Onslow, the private secretary to the Chairman of the Court of Directors of the British East India Company, proceeded by train to [[East India House]] in the [[City of London]] and passed the diamond into the care of the chairman and deputy chairman of the East India Company.\n\nThe Koh-i-Noor was formally presented to Queen Victoria on 3 July 1850 at [[Buckingham Palace]] by the deputy chairman of the East India Company.<ref name=\"keay\"/> The date had been chosen to coincide with the Company's 250th anniversary.<ref>Tarshis, p. 138.</ref>\n\n=== The Great Exhibition ===\n[[File:Kohinoor.jpg|thumb|In the armlet given to Victoria]]\nMembers of the public were given a chance to see the Koh-i-Noor when [[The Great Exhibition]] was staged at [[Hyde Park, London]], in 1851. It represented the might of the British Empire and took pride of place in the eastern part of the central gallery.<ref name=\"davis\">Davis, p. 138.</ref>\n\nIts mysterious past and advertised value of \u00a31\u20132 million drew large crowds.<ref>Young, p. 345.</ref> At first, the stone was put inside a gilded birdcage, but after complaints about its dull appearance, the Koh-i-Noor was moved to a case with black velvet and gas lamps in the hope that it would sparkle better.<ref name=\"carlyle\">{{cite web|url=http://carlyleletters.dukeupress.edu//letter/26/lt-18510511-JWC-JW-01|title=The Carlyle Letters: The Collected Letters, Volume 26|date=11 May 1851|accessdate=25 November 2017|publisher=Duke University Press|author=Jane Carlyle}}</ref> Despite this, the flawed and asymmetrical diamond still failed to please viewers.<ref name=\"rose31\">Rose, p. 31.</ref>\n\n=== 1852 re-cutting ===\nOriginally, the diamond had 169 facets and was {{convert|4.1|cm|in}} long, {{convert|3.26|cm|in}} wide, and {{convert|1.62|cm|in}} deep. It was high-domed, with a flat base and both triangular and rectangular facets, similar in overall appearance to other Mughal era diamonds which are now in the [[Iranian Crown Jewels]].<ref>Sucher and Carriere, pp. 140-141</ref>\n\nDisappointment in the appearance of the stone was not uncommon. After consulting mineralogists, including Sir [[David Brewster]], it was decided by [[Albert, Prince Consort|Prince Albert]], the husband of Queen Victoria, with the consent of the government, to polish the Koh-i-Noor. One of the largest and most famous Dutch diamond merchants, [[Coster Diamonds|Mozes Coster]], was employed for the task. He sent to London one of his most experienced artisans, Levie Benjamin Voorzanger, and his assistants.<ref name=\"davenport\"/>\n\n[[File:Re-cutting the Koh-i-Noor 1852.jpg|thumb|The 1852 re-cutting]]\nOn 17 July 1852, the cutting began at the factory of [[Garrard & Co]]. in Haymarket, using a steam-powered mill built specially for the job by [[Maudslay, Sons and Field]].<ref>{{cite book|title=The Illustrated London News|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ze1GAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA54|date=24 July 1852|publisher=Illustrated London News & Sketch Ltd|page=54}}</ref> Under the supervision of Prince Albert and the [[Arthur Wellesley, 1st Duke of Wellington|Duke of Wellington]], and the technical direction of the queen's mineralogist, [[James Tennant (mineralogist)|James Tennant]], the cutting took thirty-eight days. Albert spent a total of \u00a38,000 on the operation,<ref name=\"tweedie\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/features/7917372/The-Koh-i-Noor-diamond-robbery.html|author=Neil Tweedie|date=29 July 2010|newspaper=The Telegraph|title=The Koh-i-Noor: diamond robbery?|access-date=13 January 2016}}</ref>  which reduced the weight of the diamond from 186 old carats (191 modern carats or 38.2&nbsp;g) to its current {{convert|105.6|carat|g}}.<ref name=\"sucher\">Sucher and Carriere, pp. 124, 126.</ref> The stone measures {{convert|3.6|cm|in|abbr=on}} long, {{convert|3.2|cm|in|abbr=on}} wide, and {{convert|1.3|cm|in|1|abbr=on}} deep.<ref>Bari and Sautter, p. 178.</ref> [[Brilliant (diamond cut)|Brilliant-cut]] diamonds usually have fifty-eight facets, but the Koh-i-Noor has eight additional \"star\" facets around the [[culet]], making a total of sixty-six facets.<ref name=\"smith\"/>\n\nThe great loss of weight is to some extent accounted for by the fact that Voorzanger discovered several flaws, one especially big, that he found it necessary to cut away.<ref name=\"davenport\"/> Although Prince Albert was dissatisfied with such a huge reduction, most experts agreed that Voorzanger had made the right decision and carried out his job with impeccable skill.<ref name=\"tweedie\"/> When Queen Victoria showed the re-cut diamond to the young [[Maharaja Duleep Singh]], the Koh-i-Noor's last non-British owner, he was apparently unable to speak for several minutes afterwards.<ref name=\"sucher\"/>\n\nThe much lighter but more dazzling stone was mounted in a honeysuckle brooch and a circlet worn by the queen.<ref name=\"rose31\"/> At this time, it belonged to her personally, and was not yet part of the Crown Jewels.<ref name=\"davenport\"/> Although Victoria wore it often, she became uneasy about the way in which the diamond had been acquired. In a letter to her eldest daughter, [[Victoria, Princess Royal]], she wrote in the 1870s: \"No one feels more strongly than I do about India or how much I opposed our taking those countries and I think no more will be taken, for it is very wrong and no advantage to us. You know also how I dislike wearing the Koh-i-Noor\".<ref>Tarling, p. 27.</ref>\n\n=== Crown Jewel ===\n[[File:Queen Mary's Crown.png|thumb|upright|The Koh-i-Noor in the front cross of Queen Mary's Crown]]\nAfter Queen Victoria's death, the Koh-i-Noor was set in the [[Crown of Queen Alexandra]], the wife of [[Edward VII]], that was used to crown her at [[Coronation of King Edward VII and Queen Alexandra|their coronation]] in 1902. The diamond was transferred to [[Crown of Queen Mary|Queen Mary's Crown]] in 1911,<ref>{{Royal Collection|31704|Queen Mary's Crown}}</ref> and finally to [[Crown of Queen Elizabeth The Queen Mother|The Queen Mother's Crown]] in 1937.<ref>{{Royal Collection|31703|Queen Elizabeth The Queen Mother's Crown}}</ref> When The Queen Mother died in 2002, the crown was placed on top of her coffin for the [[lying-in-state]] and funeral.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/1907313.stm|title=Priceless gem in Queen Mother's crown|date=4 April 2002|work=BBC News|access-date=5 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nAll these crowns are on display in the [[Jewel House]] at the [[Tower of London]] with crystal replicas of the diamond set in the older crowns.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hrp.org.uk/tower-of-london/visit-us/top-things-to-see-and-do/the-crown-jewels/diamonds-and-crowns/famous-diamonds/|title=The Crown Jewels: Famous Diamonds|publisher=Historic Royal Palaces|access-date=6 January 2016}}</ref> The original bracelet given to Queen Victoria can also be seen there. A glass model of the Koh-i-Noor shows visitors how it looked when it was brought to the United Kingdom. Replicas of the diamond in this and its re-cut forms can also be seen in the 'Vault' exhibit at the [[Natural History Museum, London|Natural History Museum]] in London.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nhm.ac.uk/natureplus/blogs/whats-new/2010/04/22/glittering-finale-for-the-museum-of-life-bbc-documentary|title=Glittering finale for the Museum of Life documentary|date=22 April 2010|access-date=13 January 2016|publisher=Natural History Museum}}</ref>\n\nDuring the Second World War, the [[Crown Jewels of the United Kingdom|Crown Jewels]] were moved from their home at the Tower of London to [[Windsor Castle]].<ref>Hennessy, p. 237.</ref> In 1990, ''[[The Sunday Telegraph]]'', citing a biography of the French army general, [[Jean de Lattre de Tassigny]], by his widow, Simonne, reported that [[George VI]] hid the Koh-i-Noor at the bottom of a pond or lake near Windsor Castle, about 32&nbsp;km (20&nbsp;miles) outside London, where it remained until after the war. The only people who knew of the hiding place were the king and his librarian, Sir&nbsp;[[Owen Morshead]], who apparently revealed the secret to the general and his wife on their visit to England in 1949.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.apnewsarchive.com/1990/British-Crown-Jewels-Hidden-in-Lake-in-World-War-II-Newspaper-Says/id-eba1e1abcabd3fcb12187adde509e460|title=British Crown Jewels hidden in lake in World World II, newspaper says|agency=Associated Press|publisher=AP News Archive|date=10 June 1990|access-date=5 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Ownership dispute ==\nThe Koh-i-Noor has long been a subject of diplomatic controversy, with India, Pakistan, Iran, and Afghanistan all demanding its return from the UK at various points.{{sfn|Dalrymple|Anand|2017|p=13}}\n\n=== India ===\nThe [[Government of India]], believing the gem was rightfully theirs, first demanded the return of the Koh-i-Noor as soon as [[Indian Independence Act 1947|independence was granted]] in 1947. A second request followed in 1953, the year of the coronation of Queen [[Elizabeth II]]. Each time, the British Government rejected the claims, saying that ownership was non-negotiable.<ref name=\"tweedie\"/>\n\nIn 2000, several members of the [[Parliament of India|Indian Parliament]] signed a letter calling for the diamond to be given back to India, claiming it was taken illegally.<ref name=\"india-claim\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/south_asia/727231.stm|title=Indian MPs demand Koh-i-Noor's return |work=BBC News|date=26 April 2000|access-date=10 August 2009}}</ref> British officials said that a variety of claims meant it was impossible to establish the diamond's original owner,<ref name=\"guardian\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2000/nov/05/afghanistan|title=Taliban asks the Queen to return Koh-i-Noor gem|date=5 November 2000|author=Luke Harding|access-date=14 January 2016|newspaper=The Guardian}}</ref> and that it had been part of Britain's heritage for more than 150 years.<ref>{{cite book|author=Andrzej Jakubowski|title=State Succession in Cultural Property|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pYlwCQAAQBAJ|year=2015|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-873806-0|page=93}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2010, while visiting India, [[David Cameron]], the Prime Minister of the United Kingdom, said of returning the diamond, \"If you say yes to one you suddenly find the British Museum would be empty. I am afraid to say, it is going to have to stay put\".<ref name=\"tweedie\"/> On a subsequent visit in February 2013, he said, \"They're not having that back\".<ref name=\"huffington\">{{cite news| title=Koh-i-Noor diamond will not be returned to India, David Cameron insists|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2013/02/21/koh-i-noor-diamond-not-returned-india-david-cameron-insists-pictures_n_2732342.html|last=Nelson| first=Sara C.|work=[[The Huffington Post]]|date=21 February 2013|access-date=27 July 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2016, the [[Ministry of Culture (India)|Indian Culture Ministry]] stated it would make \"all possible efforts\" to arrange the return of the Koh-i-Noor to India.<ref>{{cite news| title=India says it wants one of the Crown Jewels back from Britain|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/04/21/world/asia/india-britain-koh-i-noor-diamond.html|author=Nida Najar|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=20 April 2016|access-date=21 April 2016}}</ref> It was despite the Indian Government earlier conceding that the diamond was a gift. The [[Solicitor General of India]] had made the announcement before the [[Supreme Court of India]] due to [[Public interest litigation in India|public interest litigation]] by a campaign group.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1160419/jsp/nation/story_80939.jsp|title=Koh-i-Noor not stolen but gifted: Centre|date=18 April 2016|access-date=20 July 2016|location=Calcutta, India|work=The Telegraph}}</ref> He said \"It was given voluntarily by Ranjit Singh to the British as compensation for help in the Sikh wars. The Koh-i-Noor is not a stolen object\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.sky.com/story/india-koh-i-noor-gem-given-to-uk-not-stolen-10248324|publisher=Sky News|date=19 April 2016|access-date=21 April 2016|title=India: Koh-i-Noor gem given to UK, not stolen}}</ref>\n\n=== Pakistan ===\nIn 1976, [[Pakistan]] asserted its ownership of the diamond, saying its return would be \"a convincing demonstration of the spirit that moved Britain voluntarily to shed its imperial encumbrances and lead the process of decolonisation\". In a letter to the Prime Minister of Pakistan, [[Zulfikar Ali Bhutto]], the Prime Minister of the United Kingdom, [[James Callaghan]], wrote, \"I need not remind you of the various hands through which the stone has passed over the past two centuries, nor that explicit provision for its transfer to the British crown was made in the peace treaty with the Maharajah of Lahore in 1849. I could not advise Her Majesty that it should be surrendered\".<ref>{{cite book|title=Pakistan Horizon|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5H9CAAAAYAAJ|volume=29|year=1976|publisher=Pakistan Institute of International Affairs|page=267}}</ref>\n\n=== Afghanistan ===\nIn 2000, the [[Taliban]]'s foreign affairs spokesman, Faiz Ahmed Faiz, said the Koh-i-Noor was the legitimate property of Afghanistan, and demanded for it to be handed over to the regime. \"The history of the diamond shows it was taken from us (Afghanistan) to India, and from there to Britain. We have a much better claim than the Indians\", he said.<ref name=\"guardian\"/> The Afghan claim derives from Shah Shuja Durrani memoirs, which states he surrendered the diamond to Ranjit Singh while Singh was having his son tortured in front of him, so argue the Maharajah of Lahore acquired the stone illegitimately.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jamal |first1=Momin |title=Kohinoor's story: from treachery to treasury |url=https://dailytimes.com.pk/26635/kohinoors-story-from-treachery-to-treasury/ |accessdate=19 June 2018 |work=Daily Times |date=26 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Possible compromises===\n\nBecause of the quadripartite dispute over the diamond's rightful ownership, there have been various compromises suggested to bring the dispute to an end. These include dividing the diamond into four, with a piece given to each of Afghanistan, India, and Pakistan, with the final piece retained by the [[British Crown]]. Another suggestion is that the jewel be housed in a special museum at the [[Wagah]] border between India and Pakistan. However this suggestion does not cater to Afghan claims, nor the reality of current British possession.{{sfn|Dalrymple|Anand|2017|p=281}} These compromises are presently unaligned with the position of the [[British Government]], which since the end of the [[British Raj]] is that the status of the diamond is 'non-negotiatable'.{{sfn|Dalrymple|Anand|2017|p=272}}\n\n== In popular culture ==\nThe Koh-i-Noor made its first appearance in popular culture in ''[[The Moonstone]]'' (1868), a 19th-century British [[epistolary novel]] by [[Wilkie Collins]], generally considered to be the first full length [[detective novel]] in the English language. In his preface to the first edition of the book, Collins says that he based his eponymous \"Moonstone\" on the histories of two stones: the [[Orlov (diamond)|Orlov]], a {{convert|189.62|carat|g|1|adj=on}} diamond in the Russian Imperial Sceptre, and the Koh-i-Noor.<ref>{{cite book|author=Wilkie Collins|title=The Moonstone: A Novel|url=https://archive.org/details/moonstoneanovel00collgoog|year=1874|publisher=Harper & Brothers|page=[https://archive.org/details/moonstoneanovel00collgoog/page/n14 8]}}</ref> In the 1966 [[Penguin Books]] edition of ''The Moonstone'', [[J. I. M. Stewart]] states that Collins used [[Charles William King|G. C. King]]'s [https://archive.org/details/naturalhistorya00kinggoog ''The Natural History, Ancient and Modern, of Precious Stones \u2026'' (1865)] to research the history of the Koh-i-Noor.<ref>Goodland, p. 136.</ref>\n\nThe Koh-i-Noor also features in [[Agatha Christie]]'s 1925 novel ''[[The Secret of Chimneys]]'' where it is hidden somewhere inside a large country house and is discovered at the end of the novel. The diamond had been stolen from the Tower of London by a Parisian gang leader who replaced it with a replica stone.<ref>{{cite book|last=Bargainnier|first=Earl F.|title=The Gentle Art of Murder: The Detective Fiction of Agatha Christie|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nEAUBOJakoQC&pg=PA89|accessdate=28 August 2018|year=1980|publisher=Popular Press|isbn=978-0-87972-159-6|page=89}}</ref>\n<!-- Please do not make a list of appearances. -->\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Golconda Diamonds]]\n* [[List of diamonds]]\n* [[List of largest rough diamonds]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Noteslist|30em}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|25em}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n{{Refbegin|30em}}\n<!-- A to G -->\n* {{cite book|first=Victor|last=Argenzio|title=Crystal Clear: The Story of Diamonds|url=https://archive.org/details/crystalclearstor00arge|url-access=registration|year=1977|publisher=David McKay Co.|isbn=978-0-679-20317-9}}\n*{{cite book|first=Ian|last=Balfour|title=Famous Diamonds|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ekzrAAAAMAAJ|year=2009|publisher=Antique Collectors' Club|isbn=978-1-85149-479-8}}\n* {{cite book|first1=Hubert|last1=Bari|first2=Violaine|last2=Sautter|title=Diamonds: In the Heart of the Earth, in the Heart of Stars, at the Heart of Power|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oS6pKwAACAAJ|year=2001|publisher=Vilo International|isbn=978-2-84576-032-5}}\n* {{cite book|first=James Andrew|last=Broun-Ramsay|title=Private Letters|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bAzgAAAAMAAJ|edition=2|year=1911|publisher=Blackwood|location=India}}\n* {{cite book|first1=William|last1=Dalrymple|first2=Anita|last2=Anand|title=Koh-i-Noor: The History of the World's Most Infamous Diamond|year=2017|publisher=Bloomsbury|isbn=978-1-408-88886-5|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JFcqDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT95|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|title=The English Regalia|first=Cyril|last=Davenport|year=1897|publisher=K. Paul, Trench, Tr\u00fcbner & Co.|url=https://archive.org/details/englishregalia00daveuoft}}\n* {{cite book|first=John R.|last=Davis|title=The Great Exhibition|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kp8hAQAAIAAJ|year=1999|publisher=Sutton|isbn=978-0-7509-1614-1}}\n* {{cite book|title=The Crown Jewels: Souvenir Guidebook|first1=Sally|last1=Dixon-Smith|first2=Sebastian|last2=Edwards|first3=Sarah|last3=Kilby|first4=Clare|last4=Murphy|first5=David|last5=Souden|first6=Jane|last6=Spooner|first7=Lucy|last7=Worsley|publisher=Historic Royal Palaces|year=2010|isbn=978-1-873993-13-2}}\n* {{cite book|first=Emily|last=Eden|title=Portraits of the Princes and People of India|year=1844|page=14|publisher=J. Dickinson & Son}}\n* {{cite book|first1=Lionel|last1=Fanthorpe|first2=Patricia|last2=Fanthorpe|title=Secrets of the World's Undiscovered Treasures|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=P7zSw4mJmKgC&pg=PA202|year=2009|publisher=Dundurn|isbn=978-1-77070-508-1}}\n* {{cite book|first=Lauren M. E.|last=Goodlad|title=The Victorian Geopolitical Aesthetic: Realism, Sovereignty, and Transnational Experience|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QzQcBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA136|year=2015|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-872827-6}}\n<!-- H to M -->\n* {{cite book|first=Elizabeth|last=Hennessy|title=A Domestic History of the Bank of England, 1930\u20131960|url=https://archive.org/details/domestichistoryo00henn|url-access=registration|page=[https://archive.org/details/domestichistoryo00henn/page/n262 237]|date=1992|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-39140-5}}\n* {{cite book|editor1-first=Karin|editor1-last=Hofmeester|editor2-first=Bernd-Stefan|editor2-last=Grewe|title=Luxury in Global Perspective: Objects and Practices, 1600\u20132000|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eu6SDQAAQBAJ|year=2016|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-1-107-10832-5}}\n* {{cite magazine|first=R. A.|last=Howie|url=http://www.minersoc.org/pages/Archive-MM/Volume_63/63-2-292.pdf|title=Book Reviews|magazine=Mineralogical Magazine|year=1999|volume=63|issue=2|publisher=Mineralogical Society of Great Britain and Ireland}}\n*{{cite journal|first=Nigel B.|last=Israel|title='The Most Unkindest Cut of All' - Recutting the Koh-i-Nur|journal=Journal of Gemmology|year=1992|volume=23|number=3|page=176|issn=0022-1252|doi=10.15506/JoG.1992.23.3.176}}\n* {{cite book|first=Anna|last=Keay|title=The Crown Jewels|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MwpjtwAACAAJ|year=2011|publisher=Thames & Hudson|isbn=978-0-500-51575-4}}\n* {{cite book|first=T. K.|last=Kurien|title=Geology and Mineral Resources of Andhra Pradesh|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=r20IAAAAIAAJ|year=1980|publisher=Geological Survey of India}}\n* {{cite book|first=Jean Marie|last=Lafont|title=Maharaja Ranjit Singh: Lord of the Five Rivers|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zjduAAAAMAAJ|year=2002|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-566111-8}}\n* {{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/sirjohnloginand00logigoog|title=Sir John Login and Duleep Singh|first=Lena Campbell|last=[[Lena Login|Login]]|year=1890|publisher=Languages Dept|location=Punjab}} \n* {{cite book|first=Kenneth J.|last=Mears|title=The Tower of London: 900 Years of English History|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=D_kgAAAAMAAJ|year=1988|publisher=Phaidon|isbn=978-0-7148-2527-4}}\n* {{cite book|first1=Kenneth J.|last1=Mears|first2=Simon|last2=Thurley|first3=Claire|last3=Murphy|title=The Crown Jewels|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=r1GJnAEACAAJ|year=1994|publisher=Historic Royal Palaces|asin=B000HHY1ZQ}}\n<!-- R to Y -->\n* {{cite book|first=P. N.|last=Rastogi|title=Ethnic Tensions in Indian Society: Explanation, Prediction, Monitoring and Control|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xBOlsFQH-toC|year=1986|publisher=Mittal Publications|isbn=978-9-997-38489-8}}\n* {{cite book|first=Tessa|last=Rose|title=The Coronation Ceremony and the Crown Jewels|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bSUTAQAAIAAJ|year=1992|publisher=HM Stationery Office|isbn=978-0-117-01361-2}}\n* {{cite book|first=Henry George|last=Smith|title=Gems and Precious Stones|url=https://archive.org/details/gemspreciousston00smitrich|year=1896|publisher=Charles Potter}}\n* {{cite book|first1=Edwin William|last1=Streeter|first2=Joseph|last2=Hatten|title=The Great Diamonds of the World|url=https://archive.org/details/greatdiamondsofw00stre|year=1882|publisher=G. Bell & Sons}}\n* {{cite journal|last1=Sucher|first1=Scott D.|last2=Carriere|first2=Dale P.|year=2008|title=The Use of Laser and X-ray Scanning to Create a Model of the Historic Koh-i-Noor Diamond|journal=Gems & Gemology|volume=44|issue=2|pages=124\u2013141|doi=10.5741/GEMS.44.2.124}}\n* {{cite journal|journal=New Zealand Journal of History|volume=15|issue=1|issn=0028-8322|date=April 1981|first=Nicholas|last=Tarling|authorlink=Nicholas Tarling|publisher=University of Auckland|url=http://www.nzjh.auckland.ac.nz/docs/1981/NZJH_15_1_03.pdf|title=The Wars of British Succession}}\n* {{cite journal |first=Dena K.|last=Tarshis |year=2000 |title=The Koh-i-Noor Diamond and its Glass Replica at the Crystal Palace Exhibition |jstor=24191006 |journal=Journal of Glass Studies |publisher=Corning Museum of Glass |volume=42 |pages=133\u2013143 |issn=0075-4250 }}\n* {{cite journal |last=Young |first=Paul |year=2007 |title=\"Carbon, Mere Carbon\": The Kohinoor, the Crystal Palace, and the Mission to Make Sense of British India |url= |journal=Nineteenth-Century Contexts |volume=29 |issue=4 |pages=343\u2013358 |doi=10.1080/08905490701768089 }}\n* {{cite book|first1=Sir George|last1=Younghusband|first2=Cyril|last2=Davenport|title=The Crown Jewels of England|url=https://archive.org/details/TheCrownJewelsOfEngland|year=1919|publisher=Cassell & Co.|asin=B00086FM86}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Koh-i-Noor Diamond}}\n* {{Wikisource-inline|links=[[s:The Folk-Lore Journal/Volume 4/A Story of the Koh-i-N\u00fbr|the Koh-i-Noor]]}}\n\n{{Crown Jewels of the United Kingdom}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Koh-I-Noor}}\n[[Category:Crown Jewels of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Jewels of the Mughal Empire]]\n[[Category:Diamonds originating in India]]\n[[Category:History of India]]\n[[Category:History of Andhra Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Sikh Empire]]\n[[Category:1739 in Asia]]\n[[Category:Persian words and phrases]]\n[[Category:Golconda diamonds]]\n", "text_old": "{{Redirect|Kohinoor}}\n{{short description|One of the largest cut diamonds in the world, now part of the British Crown Jewels}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2011}}\n{{Infobox gem\n| name    = Koh-i-Noor\n| image   = Koh-i-Noor old version copy.jpg\n| image2  = Koh-i-Noor new version copy.jpg\n| caption = Glass replicas of the diamond before (upside down) and after it was re-cut in 1852\n| weight  = {{convert|105.602|carat|g}}{{efn|name=\"weight\"|Weights from {{frac|82|3|4}} to {{frac|122|3|4}} carats have been erroneously published since the 19th century.<ref name=\"israel\">Israel, p. 176.</ref> Until 1992, the official weight of the Koh-i-Noor was 108.93 metric carats,<ref>Balfour, p. 184.</ref> but this figure has been revised to 105.602 metric carats,<ref name=\"rose31\"/> or {{frac|102|13|16}} old English carats.<ref name=\"israel\"/>}}\n| dimensions = {{convert|3.6|cm|in|abbr=on}} long<br/>{{convert|3.2|cm|in|abbr=on}} wide<br/>{{convert|1.3|cm|in|1|abbr=on}} deep\n| colour  = D (colourless)<ref name=\"sucher126\">Sucher and Carriere, p. 126.</ref>\n| diamond_type = IIa<ref name=\"sucher126\"/>\n| cut = Oval brilliant\n| facets = 66<ref name=\"smith\">Smith, p. 77.</ref>\n| mine = [[Kollur Mine]]\n|country = [[India]]\n| cutter = Levie Benjamin Voorzanger\n| owner = Queen [[Elizabeth&nbsp;II]] in right of [[the Crown]]<ref>{{Cite Hansard |jurisdiction=United Kingdom |house=House of Commons |title=Crown Jewels |url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/written_answers/1992/jul/16/crown-jewels#column_944w |date=16 July 1992 |volume=211 |column=944W }}</ref>\n| value = Not insured<ref>{{Cite Hansard |jurisdiction=United Kingdom |house=House of Commons |title=Royal Residences |url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/written_answers/2003/jun/19/royal-residences#S6CV0407P0_20030619_CWA_85 |date=19 June 2003 |column=353W |volume=407 }}</ref>\n}}\nThe '''Koh-i-Noor''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02cc|k|\u0259\u028a|\u026a|\u02c8|n|\u028a\u0259r}}; {{lit}} \"Mountain of light\"),<ref name=\"EB2008\">{{cite encyclopedia |title=Koh-i-Noor|encyclopedia=Britannica Concise Encyclopedia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ea-bAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA1046 |date=2008 |publisher=[[Encyclopaedia Britannica]] |isbn=9781593394929 |page=1046 |language=English|quote=The Koh-i-noor (Hindi for \"mountain of light\") was acquired by the British in 1849 and became part of the Crown Jewels of Queen Victoria.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.collinsdictionary.com/dictionary/english/koh-i-noor|title=Definition of 'Koh-i-noor'|accessdate=26 November 2017|author=Collins English Dictionary|publisher=HarperCollins}}</ref> also spelt '''Kohinoor''' and '''Koh-i-Nur''', is one of the [[List of diamonds|largest cut diamonds]] in the world, weighing {{convert|105.6|carat|g}}.{{efn|name=\"weight\"}} It is part of the [[British Crown Jewels]].\n\nProbably mined in [[Kollur Mine]], India, during the period of the [[Delhi Sultanate]], there is no record of its original weight \u2013 but the earliest well-attested weight is 186 old carats (191 metric carats or 38.2&nbsp;g). The diamond was part of the [[Mughal emperors|Mughal]] [[Peacock Throne]]. It changed hands between various factions in south and west Asia, until being ceded to [[Queen Victoria]] after the [[Second Anglo-Sikh War|British annexation]] of the [[Punjab Province (British India)|Punjab]] in 1849.\n\nOriginally, the stone was of a similar cut to other [[Mughal Empire|Mughal-era]] diamonds, like the [[Darya-i-Noor]], which are now in the [[Iranian Crown Jewels]]. In 1851, it went on display at the [[Great Exhibition]] in London, but the lacklustre cut failed to impress viewers. [[Albert, Prince Consort|Prince Albert]], husband of Queen Victoria, ordered it to be re-cut as an oval brilliant by [[Coster Diamonds]]. By modern standards, the culet (point at the bottom of a gemstone) is unusually broad, giving the impression of a black hole when the stone is viewed head-on; it is nevertheless regarded by [[gemology|gemologists]] as \"full of life\".<ref>Howie, p. 293.</ref>\n\nBecause its history involves a great deal of fighting between men, the Koh-i-Noor acquired a reputation within the [[British royal family]] for bringing bad luck to any man who wears it.<!--cited end of paragraph--> Since arriving in the UK, it has only been worn by female members of the family.<ref>Mears, et al., p. 27.</ref> Victoria wore the stone in a brooch and a circlet. After she died in 1901, it was set in the [[Crown of Queen Alexandra]], wife of [[Edward VII]]. It was transferred to the [[Crown of Queen Mary]] in 1911, and finally to the [[Crown of Queen Elizabeth The Queen Mother|Crown of Queen Elizabeth]] (later known at the Queen Mother) in 1937 for her coronation as Queen consort.\n\nToday, the diamond is on public display in the [[Jewel House]] at the [[Tower of London]], where it is seen by millions of visitors each year. The governments of India, Pakistan, Iran, and Afghanistan have all claimed rightful ownership of the Koh-i-Noor and demanded its return ever since India gained independence from the UK in 1947. The British government insists the gem was obtained legally under the terms of the [[Treaty of Lahore#Text of the 1849 Last Treaty of Lahore|Last Treaty of Lahore]] and has rejected the claims.<!-- all cited within article body -->\n\n== History ==\n=== Origin ===\nThe diamond may have been mined from [[Kollur Mine]],<ref>Fanthorpe, p. 202.</ref><ref>Mears (1988), p. 100.</ref> a series of {{convert|4|m|ft|adj=on}} deep [[Gravel pit|gravel-clay pits]] on the banks of [[Krishna River]] in the [[Golconda Sultanate|Golconda]] (present-day <!--It is in Andhra Pradesh not Telangana-->[[Andhra Pradesh]]<!--It is not in Telangana-->), [[India]].<ref>Kurien, p. 112.</ref> It is impossible to know exactly when or where it was found, and many unverifiable theories exist as to its original owner.<ref name=\"rose32\">Rose, p. 32.</ref>\n\n=== Early history ===\n[[Babur]], the [[Turco-Mongol]] founder of the [[Mughal Empire]], wrote about a \"famous\" diamond that weighed just over 187 old carats \u2013&nbsp;approximately the size of the 186-carat Koh-i-Noor.<ref>Streeter, pp. 116\u2013117, 130.</ref> Some historians think Babur's diamond is the earliest reliable reference to the Koh-i-Noor.<ref>Lafont, p. 48.</ref> According to his diary, it was acquired by [[Alauddin Khalji]], second ruler of the [[Khalji dynasty]] of the [[Delhi Sultanate]], when he [[Alauddin Khalji#Marwar and southern campaigns, 1307\u20131313|invaded the kingdoms of southern India]] at the beginning of the 14th&nbsp;century and was probably in the possession of [[Kakatiya dynasty]].<ref>{{cite book |title=India Before Europe |last1=Asher |first1=Catherine B. |last2=Talbot |first2=Cynthia |date=2006 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-0-52180-904-7 |page=40 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZvaGuaJIJgoC&pg=PA40# |accessdate=20 February 2019 |language=en}}</ref> It later passed to succeeding dynasties of the Sultanate, and Babur received the diamond in 1526 as a tribute for his conquest of [[Delhi]] and [[Agra]] at the [[Battle of Panipat (1526)|Battle of Panipat]].<ref name=\"rose32\"/>\n\n[[Shah Jahan]], the fifth Mughal emperor, had the stone placed into his ornate [[Peacock Throne]]. In 1658, his son and successor, [[Aurangzeb]], confined the ailing emperor to [[Agra Fort]]. While in the possession of Aurangzeb, it was allegedly cut by Hortenso Borgia, a Venetian [[lapidary]], reducing the weight of the large stone to {{convert|186|carat|g}}.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article96503185 |title=Fascinating history of world's best diamonds|newspaper=[[The Northern Star]] |location=Lismore, New South Wales |date=30 May 1953 | author=Leela Kohli|accessdate=31 August 2013 |page=6 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> For this carelessness, Borgia was reprimanded and fined 10,000 [[rupee]]s.<ref>Younghusband and Davenport, pp. 53\u201357.</ref> According to recent research, the story of Borgia cutting the diamond is not correct, and most probably mixed up with the [[Orlov (diamond)|Orlov]], part of [[Catherine the Great]]'s imperial Russian sceptre in the Kremlin.<ref name=\"bbc.com\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-india-38218308|title=Koh-i-Noor: Six myths about a priceless diamond|work=BBC News|date=9 December 2016|accessdate=30 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Maharaja Ranjit singh's treasure.jpg|thumb|upright|One of Ranjit Singh's favourite horses with the head of his stables. His jewels are shown, to scale, including the Koh-i-Noor (top centre).<ref>Eden, p. 14.</ref>]]\nFollowing the 1739 invasion of Delhi by [[Nadir Shah]], the [[Afsharid dynasty|Afsharid Shah of Persia]], the treasury of the Mughal Empire was looted by his army in an organised and thorough acquisition of the Mughal nobility's wealth.<ref name=\"davenport\"/> Along with millions of [[rupee]]s and an assortment of historic jewels, the Shah also carried away the Koh-i-Noor.<ref name=\"siebenhuner\">Kim Siebenh\u00fcner in Hofmeester and Grewe, pp. 27\u201328.</ref> He exclaimed ''Koh-i-Noor!'', Persian for \"Mountain of Light\", when he obtained the famous stone.<ref>Argenzio, p. 42.</ref> One of his consorts said, \"If a strong man were to throw four stones \u2013 one north, one south, one east, one west, and a fifth stone up into the air \u2013 and if the space between them were to be filled with gold, all would not equal the value of the Koh-i-Noor\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2016/feb/16/koh-i-noor-diamond-britain-illegally-india-pakistan-afghanistan-history-tower|title=The Koh-i-Noor diamond is in Britain illegally. But it should still stay there|author=Anita Anand|work=The Guardian|date=16 February 2016|accessdate=8 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nAfter Nadir Shah was killed and [[Division of the Afsharid Empire|his empire collapsed]] in 1747, the Koh-i-Noor fell to his grandson, who in 1751 gave it to [[Ahmad Shah Durrani]], founder of the [[Afghan Empire]], in return for his support.<ref name=\"siebenhuner\"/> One of Ahmed's descendants, [[Shuja Shah Durrani]], wore a bracelet containing the Koh-i-Noor on the occasion of [[Mountstuart Elphinstone]]'s visit to [[Peshawar]] in 1808.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Asiatic Journal and Monthly Register for British India and its Dependencies|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wjk9AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA177|volume=27|year=1838|publisher=W. H. Allen & Co.|page=177}}</ref> A year later, Shuja formed an alliance with the United Kingdom to help defend against a possible invasion of Afghanistan by Russia.<ref>{{cite book|author=William Dalrymple|title=Return of a King: The Battle for Afghanistan|isbn=978-1-408-8183-05 |publisher=Bloomsbury|year=2012|page=5}}</ref> He was quickly overthrown, but fled with the diamond to [[Lahore]], where [[Ranjit Singh]], founder of the [[Sikh Empire]], in return for his hospitality, insisted upon the gem being given to him, and he took possession of it in 1813.<ref name=\"davenport\">Davenport, pp. 57\u201359.</ref>\n\n=== In Ranjit Singh's possession ===\n\nRanjit Singh had the diamond examined by jewelers of Lahore for two days to ensure that Shuja had not tricked him. After the jewelers confirmed its genuineness, he donated 125,000 rupees to Shuja. Ranjit Singh then asked the principal jewelers of Amritsar to estimate the diamond's value; the jewelers declared that the value of the diamond was \"far beyond all computation\".{{sfn|Dalrymple|Anand|2017|p=83}} Ranjit Singh then fixed the diamond in the front of his turban, and paraded on an elephant to enable his subjects to see the diamond.{{sfn|Dalrymple|Anand|2017|pp=83-84}} He used to wear it as an armlet during major festivals such as [[Diwali]] and [[Dusserah]], and took it with him during travel. He would exhibit it to prominent visitors, especially British officers.{{sfn|Dalrymple|Anand|2017|p=84}}\n\nOne day, Ranjit Singh asked the diamond's former owners - Shuja and his wife Wafa Begum - to estimate its value. Wafa Begum replied that if a strong man threw a stone in four cardinal directions and vertically, Koh-i-Noor would be worth more than the gold and precious stones filled in the space. Ranjit Singh grew paranoid about the Koh-i-Noor being stolen, because in the past, another valuable jewel had been stolen from him while he was intoxicated. He kept the diamond within a high-security facility at the [[Gobindgarh Fort]] when it was not in use. When the diamond was to be transported, it was placed in a [[pannier]] on a guarded camel; 39 other camels with identical panniers were included in the convoy; the diamond was always placed on the first camel immediately behind the guards, but great secrecy was maintained regarding which camel carried it.{{sfn|Dalrymple|Anand|2017|p=84}} Only Ranjit Singh's treasurer Misr Beli Ram knew which camel carried the diamond.{{sfn|Dalrymple|Anand|2017|p=106}}\n\nIn June 1839, Ranjit Singh suffered his third [[stroke]], and it became apparent that he would die soon. On his deathbed, he started giving away his valuable possessions to religious charities, and appointed his eldest son [[Kharak Singh]] as his successor. A day before his death, on 26 June 1839, a major argument broke out between his courtiers regarding the fate of Koh-i-Noor.{{sfn|Dalrymple|Anand|2017|p=91}} Ranjit Singh himself was too weak to speak, and communicated using gestures. Bhai Gobind Ram, the head [[Brahmin]] of Ranjit Singh, insisted that the king had willed Koh-i-Noor and other jewels to the [[Jagannath Temple, Puri|Jagannath Temple]] in [[Puri]]: the king apparently supported this claim through gestures, as recorded in his court chronicle ''Umdat ul-Tawarikh''.{{sfn|Dalrymple|Anand|2017|pp=91-92}} However, treasurer Beli Ram insisted that it was a state property rather than Ranjit Singh's personal property, and therefore, should be handed over to Kharak Singh.{{sfn|Dalrymple|Anand|2017|p=92}}\n\nAfter Ranjit Singh's death, Beli Ram refused to send the diamond to the temple, and hid it in his vaults.{{sfn|Dalrymple|Anand|2017|p=107}} Meanwhile, Kharak Singh and prime minister [[Dhian Singh]] also issued orders stating that the diamond should not be taken out of Lahore.{{sfn|Dalrymple|Anand|2017|p=108}}\n\n=== In Gulab Singh's possession ===\nOn 8 October 1839 the new emperor Kharak Singh, was overthrown in a coup by his prime minister Dhian Singh. The prime minister's brother [[Gulab Singh]], [[Raja]] of [[Jammu]], came into possession of the Koh-i-Noor.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.pt/books?id=7dymBAAAQBAJ&pg=PT121&lpg=PT121&dq=koh+i+noor+dogra&source=bl&ots=xGtrOZwhsL&sig=ACfU3U2uSFXCyDt560eRW3WZ1olxzCSo0Q&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=koh%20i%20noor%20dogra&f=false|title=The Koh-i-noor Diamond|last=Amini|first=Iradj|date=2013-06-01|publisher=Roli Books Private Limited|isbn=978-93-5194-035-7}}</ref> Kharak Singh later died in prison, soon followed by the mysterious death of his son and successor [[Nau Nihal Singh]] on 5 November 1840. Gulab Singh held onto the stone until January 1841, when he presented it to emperor [[Sher Singh]] in order to win his favour,<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.pt/books?id=P4bNDUFhI9IC&pg=PA166&lpg=PA166&dq=gulab+singh+koh+i+noor&source=bl&ots=6CRR_w0gk7&sig=ACfU3U1bjyFKE8gZoefM145d17g0hrm9Fw&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=gulab%20singh%20koh%20i%20noor&f=false|title=History of Koh-i-Noor, Darya-i-Noor, and Taimur's Ruby|date=1985|publisher=Atlantic Publishers & Distri}}</ref> after his brother Dhian Singh negotiated a ceasefire between Sher Singh and the overthrown empress [[Chand Kaur]]. Gulab Singh had attempted to defend the widowed empress at her fort in Lahore, during two days of conflict and shelling by Sher Singh and his troops.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.pt/books?id=HBOMDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA177&lpg=PA177&dq=chand+kaur+gulab+singh+fort&source=bl&ots=vc28pFQqj6&sig=ACfU3U0kDzDxjZiEA8fveSYl2BFohl6SKg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjAtdWx8bfmAhVGcBQKHTowB50Q6AEwEXoECAsQAQ#v=onepage&q=chand%20kaur%20gulab%20singh%20fort&f=false|title=Emperor of the Five Rivers: The Life and Times of Maharajah Ranjit Singh|last=Sheikh|first=Mohamed|date=2017-03-17|publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing|isbn=978-1-78673-095-4}}</ref> Despite handing over the Koh-i-noor, Gulab Singh as a result of the ceasefire returned safely to Jammu with a wealth of gold and other jewels taken from the treasury.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.pt/books?id=OzZzFm4pLWQC&pg=PA185&lpg=PA185&dq=chand+kaur+jammu&source=bl&ots=-AwTWgGwdA&sig=ACfU3U1YrV8iDbkBiqS3YCOK6iRWNyDxbg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj63syz8rfmAhWGA2MBHbxsDAA4ChDoATAGegQIBhAB#v=onepage&q=chand%20kaur%20jammu&f=false|title=Advance Study in the History of Modern India (Volume-2: 1803-1920)|last=Chhabra|first=G. S.|date=2005|publisher=Lotus Press|isbn=978-81-89093-07-5}}</ref>\n\n==== Worn by child emperor Duleep Singh ====\nOn 15 September 1843, both Sher Singh and prime minister Dhian Singh were assassinated in a coup led by Ajit Singh Sandhawalia. However, the next day in a counter coup led by Dhian's son Hira Singh the assassins were killed. Aged 24, Hira Singh succeeded his father as prime minister, and installed the five year old infant Duleep Singh as emperor. The Koh-i-noor was now fastened to the arm of the child emperor in court at Lahore. Duleep Singh and his mother empress [[Jind Kaur]], had till then resided in Jammu, the kingdom governed by Gulab Singh.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.pt/books?id=EoJoDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA115&lpg=PA115&dq=Koh-i-Noor+sher+singh&source=bl&ots=eMkin6tPB-&sig=ACfU3U3x6foG-i11WhDLs7oa4TD_2zpK7Q&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjikrjop7bmAhWIkxQKHRovBN4Q6AEwGHoECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=Koh-i-Noor%20sher%20singh&f=false|title=Kohinoor: The Story of the World\u00d5s Most Infamous Diamond|last=Dalrymple|first=William|last2=Anand|first2=Anita|date=2016|publisher=Juggernaut Books|isbn=978-93-86228-08-6}}</ref>\n\nFollowing his nephew Prime Minister Hira Singh's assassination on 27 March 1844, and the subsequent outbreak of the [[First Anglo-Sikh War]], Gulab Singh himself led the Sikh empire as its prime minister, and despite defeat in the war, he became the first [[Maharaja]] of [[Jammu and Kashmir (princely state)|Jammu and Kashmir]] on 16 March 1846, under the [[Treaty of Amritsar (1846)|Treaty of Amritsar]].\n\n=== Acquisition by Queen Victoria ===\nOn 29 March 1849, following the conclusion of the [[Second Anglo-Sikh War]], the Kingdom of [[Punjab Province (British India)|Punjab]] was formally annexed to [[Company rule in India|Company rule]], and the [[Treaty of Lahore#Text of the 1849 Last Treaty of Lahore|Last Treaty of Lahore]] was signed, officially ceding the Koh-i-Noor to [[Queen Victoria]] and the Maharaja's other assets to the company. Article III of the treaty read: \"The gem called the Koh-i-Noor, which was taken from Shah Sooja-ool-moolk by Maharajah Ranjeet Singh, shall be surrendered by the Maharajah of Lahore to the Queen of England (''sic'')\".<ref>Login, p. 126.</ref>\n\nThe lead signatory of the treaty for the eleven-year-old Maharaja Duleep Singh was his commander-in-chief [[Tej Singh]], a loyalist of Maharaja [[Gulab Singh]] who had previously been in possession of the Koh-i-noor and gained [[Kashmir]] from the Sikh empire, via treaty with Britain, following the [[First Anglo-Sikh War]].\n\nThe [[Governor-General of India|Governor-General]] in charge of the ratification of this treaty was the [[James Broun-Ramsay, 1st Marquess of Dalhousie|Marquess of Dalhousie]]. The manner of his aiding in the transfer of the diamond was criticized even by some of his contemporaries in Britain. Although some thought it should have been presented as a gift to Queen Victoria by the East India Company, it is clear that Dalhousie believed the stone was a spoil of war, and treated it accordingly, ensuring that it was officially surrendered to her by [[Duleep Singh]], the youngest son of Ranjit Singh.<ref>Broun-Ramsay, pp. 87\u201388</ref> The presentation of the Koh-i-Noor by the East India Company to the queen was the latest in a long history of transfers of the diamond as a coveted spoil of war.<ref name=\"keay\">Keay, pp. 156\u2013158</ref> Duleep Singh had been placed in the guardianship of Dr John Login, a surgeon in the British Army serving in the [[Presidency of Bengal]]. Duleep Singh would move to England in 1854.\n\n==== Journey to the United Kingdom ====\n[[File:Croquis du Koh-i-Noor d'apr\u00e8s Tavernier.jpg|thumb|Diagram of the pre-1852 cut.<ref>Valentine Ball in Jean Baptiste Tavernier, ''Travels in India'', 1889, Macmillan, vol. II, Appendix, plate VI.</ref><br /><br />'''Fig I'''. Shaded area is the base.<br />'''Fig II'''. A: flaw; B and C: notches cut to hold stone in a setting; D: flaw created by fracture at E; F: fracture created by a blow; G: unpolished cleavage plane; H: basal cleavage plane.<br />'''Fig III'''. Opposite side, showing facets and peak of the \"Mountain of Light\"]]\nIn due course, the Governor-General received the Koh-i-Noor from Dr Login, who had been appointed Governor of the Citadel, on 6 April 1848 under a receipt dated 7 December 1849, in the presence of members of the Board of Administration for the affairs of the Punjab: [[Henry Montgomery Lawrence|Sir Henry Lawrence]] (President), C. G. Mansel, [[John Lawrence, 1st Baron Lawrence|John Lawrence]] and Sir Henry Elliot (Secretary to the Government of India).\n\nLegend in the Lawrence family has it that before the voyage, John Lawrence left the jewel in his waistcoat pocket when it was sent to be laundered, and was most grateful when it was returned promptly by the [[valet]] who found it.<ref name=\"Birdwood1946\">{{cite book|author=William Riddell Birdwood|title=In My Time: Recollections and Anecdotes|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9GwgAAAAMAAJ|year=1946|publisher=Skeffington & Son|page=85}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 February 1850, the jewel was sealed in a small iron safe inside a red dispatch box, both sealed with red tape and a wax seal and kept in a chest at Bombay Treasury awaiting a steamer ship from China. It was then sent to England for presentation to Queen Victoria in the care of Captain J. Ramsay and Brevet Lt. Col F. Mackeson under tight security arrangements, one of which was the placement of the dispatch box in a larger iron safe. They departed from Bombay on 6 April on board HMS ''Medea'', captained by Captain Lockyer.\n\nThe ship had a difficult voyage: an outbreak of [[cholera]] on board when the ship was in [[Mauritius]] had the locals demanding its departure, and they asked their governor to open fire on the vessel and destroy it if there was no response. Shortly afterwards, the vessel was hit by a severe gale that blew for some 12 hours.\n\nOn arrival in Britain on 29 June, the passengers and mail were unloaded in [[Plymouth]], but the Koh-i-Noor stayed on board until the ship reached [[Spithead]], near [[Portsmouth]], on 1 July. The next morning, Ramsay and Mackeson, in the company of Mr Onslow, the private secretary to the Chairman of the Court of Directors of the British East India Company, proceeded by train to [[East India House]] in the [[City of London]] and passed the diamond into the care of the chairman and deputy chairman of the East India Company.\n\nThe Koh-i-Noor was formally presented to Queen Victoria on 3 July 1850 at [[Buckingham Palace]] by the deputy chairman of the East India Company.<ref name=\"keay\"/> The date had been chosen to coincide with the Company's 250th anniversary.<ref>Tarshis, p. 138.</ref>\n\n=== The Great Exhibition ===\n[[File:Kohinoor.jpg|thumb|In the armlet given to Victoria]]\nMembers of the public were given a chance to see the Koh-i-Noor when [[The Great Exhibition]] was staged at [[Hyde Park, London]], in 1851. It represented the might of the British Empire and took pride of place in the eastern part of the central gallery.<ref name=\"davis\">Davis, p. 138.</ref>\n\nIts mysterious past and advertised value of \u00a31\u20132 million drew large crowds.<ref>Young, p. 345.</ref> At first, the stone was put inside a gilded birdcage, but after complaints about its dull appearance, the Koh-i-Noor was moved to a case with black velvet and gas lamps in the hope that it would sparkle better.<ref name=\"carlyle\">{{cite web|url=http://carlyleletters.dukeupress.edu//letter/26/lt-18510511-JWC-JW-01|title=The Carlyle Letters: The Collected Letters, Volume 26|date=11 May 1851|accessdate=25 November 2017|publisher=Duke University Press|author=Jane Carlyle}}</ref> Despite this, the flawed and asymmetrical diamond still failed to please viewers.<ref name=\"rose31\">Rose, p. 31.</ref>\n\n=== 1852 re-cutting ===\nOriginally, the diamond had 169 facets and was {{convert|4.1|cm|in}} long, {{convert|3.26|cm|in}} wide, and {{convert|1.62|cm|in}} deep. It was high-domed, with a flat base and both triangular and rectangular facets, similar in overall appearance to other Mughal era diamonds which are now in the [[Iranian Crown Jewels]].<ref>Sucher and Carriere, pp. 140-141</ref>\n\nDisappointment in the appearance of the stone was not uncommon. After consulting mineralogists, including Sir [[David Brewster]], it was decided by [[Albert, Prince Consort|Prince Albert]], the husband of Queen Victoria, with the consent of the government, to polish the Koh-i-Noor. One of the largest and most famous Dutch diamond merchants, [[Coster Diamonds|Mozes Coster]], was employed for the task. He sent to London one of his most experienced artisans, Levie Benjamin Voorzanger, and his assistants.<ref name=\"davenport\"/>\n\n[[File:Re-cutting the Koh-i-Noor 1852.jpg|thumb|The 1852 re-cutting]]\nOn 17 July 1852, the cutting began at the factory of [[Garrard & Co]]. in Haymarket, using a steam-powered mill built specially for the job by [[Maudslay, Sons and Field]].<ref>{{cite book|title=The Illustrated London News|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ze1GAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA54|date=24 July 1852|publisher=Illustrated London News & Sketch Ltd|page=54}}</ref> Under the supervision of Prince Albert and the [[Arthur Wellesley, 1st Duke of Wellington|Duke of Wellington]], and the technical direction of the queen's mineralogist, [[James Tennant (mineralogist)|James Tennant]], the cutting took thirty-eight days. Albert spent a total of \u00a38,000 on the operation,<ref name=\"tweedie\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/features/7917372/The-Koh-i-Noor-diamond-robbery.html|author=Neil Tweedie|date=29 July 2010|newspaper=The Telegraph|title=The Koh-i-Noor: diamond robbery?|access-date=13 January 2016}}</ref>  which reduced the weight of the diamond from 186 old carats (191 modern carats or 38.2&nbsp;g) to its current {{convert|105.6|carat|g}}.<ref name=\"sucher\">Sucher and Carriere, pp. 124, 126.</ref> The stone measures {{convert|3.6|cm|in|abbr=on}} long, {{convert|3.2|cm|in|abbr=on}} wide, and {{convert|1.3|cm|in|1|abbr=on}} deep.<ref>Bari and Sautter, p. 178.</ref> [[Brilliant (diamond cut)|Brilliant-cut]] diamonds usually have fifty-eight facets, but the Koh-i-Noor has eight additional \"star\" facets around the [[culet]], making a total of sixty-six facets.<ref name=\"smith\"/>\n\nThe great loss of weight is to some extent accounted for by the fact that Voorzanger discovered several flaws, one especially big, that he found it necessary to cut away.<ref name=\"davenport\"/> Although Prince Albert was dissatisfied with such a huge reduction, most experts agreed that Voorzanger had made the right decision and carried out his job with impeccable skill.<ref name=\"tweedie\"/> When Queen Victoria showed the re-cut diamond to the young [[Maharaja Duleep Singh]], the Koh-i-Noor's last non-British owner, he was apparently unable to speak for several minutes afterwards.<ref name=\"sucher\"/>\n\nThe much lighter but more dazzling stone was mounted in a honeysuckle brooch and a circlet worn by the queen.<ref name=\"rose31\"/> At this time, it belonged to her personally, and was not yet part of the Crown Jewels.<ref name=\"davenport\"/> Although Victoria wore it often, she became uneasy about the way in which the diamond had been acquired. In a letter to her eldest daughter, [[Victoria, Princess Royal]], she wrote in the 1870s: \"No one feels more strongly than I do about India or how much I opposed our taking those countries and I think no more will be taken, for it is very wrong and no advantage to us. You know also how I dislike wearing the Koh-i-Noor\".<ref>Tarling, p. 27.</ref>\n\n=== Crown Jewel ===\n[[File:Queen Mary's Crown.png|thumb|upright|The Koh-i-Noor in the front cross of Queen Mary's Crown]]\nAfter Queen Victoria's death, the Koh-i-Noor was set in the [[Crown of Queen Alexandra]], the wife of [[Edward VII]], that was used to crown her at [[Coronation of King Edward VII and Queen Alexandra|their coronation]] in 1902. The diamond was transferred to [[Crown of Queen Mary|Queen Mary's Crown]] in 1911,<ref>{{Royal Collection|31704|Queen Mary's Crown}}</ref> and finally to [[Crown of Queen Elizabeth The Queen Mother|The Queen Mother's Crown]] in 1937.<ref>{{Royal Collection|31703|Queen Elizabeth The Queen Mother's Crown}}</ref> When The Queen Mother died in 2002, the crown was placed on top of her coffin for the [[lying-in-state]] and funeral.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/1907313.stm|title=Priceless gem in Queen Mother's crown|date=4 April 2002|work=BBC News|access-date=5 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nAll these crowns are on display in the [[Jewel House]] at the [[Tower of London]] with crystal replicas of the diamond set in the older crowns.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hrp.org.uk/tower-of-london/visit-us/top-things-to-see-and-do/the-crown-jewels/diamonds-and-crowns/famous-diamonds/|title=The Crown Jewels: Famous Diamonds|publisher=Historic Royal Palaces|access-date=6 January 2016}}</ref> The original bracelet given to Queen Victoria can also be seen there. A glass model of the Koh-i-Noor shows visitors how it looked when it was brought to the United Kingdom. Replicas of the diamond in this and its re-cut forms can also be seen in the 'Vault' exhibit at the [[Natural History Museum, London|Natural History Museum]] in London.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nhm.ac.uk/natureplus/blogs/whats-new/2010/04/22/glittering-finale-for-the-museum-of-life-bbc-documentary|title=Glittering finale for the Museum of Life documentary|date=22 April 2010|access-date=13 January 2016|publisher=Natural History Museum}}</ref>\n\nDuring the Second World War, the [[Crown Jewels of the United Kingdom|Crown Jewels]] were moved from their home at the Tower of London to [[Windsor Castle]].<ref>Hennessy, p. 237.</ref> In 1990, ''[[The Sunday Telegraph]]'', citing a biography of the French army general, [[Jean de Lattre de Tassigny]], by his widow, Simonne, reported that [[George VI]] hid the Koh-i-Noor at the bottom of a pond or lake near Windsor Castle, about 32&nbsp;km (20&nbsp;miles) outside London, where it remained until after the war. The only people who knew of the hiding place were the king and his librarian, Sir&nbsp;[[Owen Morshead]], who apparently revealed the secret to the general and his wife on their visit to England in 1949.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.apnewsarchive.com/1990/British-Crown-Jewels-Hidden-in-Lake-in-World-War-II-Newspaper-Says/id-eba1e1abcabd3fcb12187adde509e460|title=British Crown Jewels hidden in lake in World World II, newspaper says|agency=Associated Press|publisher=AP News Archive|date=10 June 1990|access-date=5 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Ownership dispute ==\nThe Koh-i-Noor has long been a subject of diplomatic controversy, with India, Pakistan, Iran, and Afghanistan all demanding its return from the UK at various points.{{sfn|Dalrymple|Anand|2017|p=13}}\n\n=== India ===\nThe [[Government of India]], believing the gem was rightfully theirs, first demanded the return of the Koh-i-Noor as soon as [[Indian Independence Act 1947|independence was granted]] in 1947. A second request followed in 1953, the year of the coronation of Queen [[Elizabeth II]]. Each time, the British Government rejected the claims, saying that ownership was non-negotiable.<ref name=\"tweedie\"/>\n\nIn 2000, several members of the [[Parliament of India|Indian Parliament]] signed a letter calling for the diamond to be given back to India, claiming it was taken illegally.<ref name=\"india-claim\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/south_asia/727231.stm|title=Indian MPs demand Koh-i-Noor's return |work=BBC News|date=26 April 2000|access-date=10 August 2009}}</ref> British officials said that a variety of claims meant it was impossible to establish the diamond's original owner,<ref name=\"guardian\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2000/nov/05/afghanistan|title=Taliban asks the Queen to return Koh-i-Noor gem|date=5 November 2000|author=Luke Harding|access-date=14 January 2016|newspaper=The Guardian}}</ref> and that it had been part of Britain's heritage for more than 150 years.<ref>{{cite book|author=Andrzej Jakubowski|title=State Succession in Cultural Property|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pYlwCQAAQBAJ|year=2015|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-873806-0|page=93}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2010, while visiting India, [[David Cameron]], the Prime Minister of the United Kingdom, said of returning the diamond, \"If you say yes to one you suddenly find the British Museum would be empty. I am afraid to say, it is going to have to stay put\".<ref name=\"tweedie\"/> On a subsequent visit in February 2013, he said, \"They're not having that back\".<ref name=\"huffington\">{{cite news| title=Koh-i-Noor diamond will not be returned to India, David Cameron insists|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2013/02/21/koh-i-noor-diamond-not-returned-india-david-cameron-insists-pictures_n_2732342.html|last=Nelson| first=Sara C.|work=[[The Huffington Post]]|date=21 February 2013|access-date=27 July 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2016, the [[Ministry of Culture (India)|Indian Culture Ministry]] stated it would make \"all possible efforts\" to arrange the return of the Koh-i-Noor to India.<ref>{{cite news| title=India says it wants one of the Crown Jewels back from Britain|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/04/21/world/asia/india-britain-koh-i-noor-diamond.html|author=Nida Najar|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=20 April 2016|access-date=21 April 2016}}</ref> It was despite the Indian Government earlier conceding that the diamond was a gift. The [[Solicitor General of India]] had made the announcement before the [[Supreme Court of India]] due to [[Public interest litigation in India|public interest litigation]] by a campaign group.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1160419/jsp/nation/story_80939.jsp|title=Koh-i-Noor not stolen but gifted: Centre|date=18 April 2016|access-date=20 July 2016|location=Calcutta, India|work=The Telegraph}}</ref> He said \"It was given voluntarily by Ranjit Singh to the British as compensation for help in the Sikh wars. The Koh-i-Noor is not a stolen object\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.sky.com/story/india-koh-i-noor-gem-given-to-uk-not-stolen-10248324|publisher=Sky News|date=19 April 2016|access-date=21 April 2016|title=India: Koh-i-Noor gem given to UK, not stolen}}</ref>\n\n=== Pakistan ===\nIn 1976, [[Pakistan]] asserted its ownership of the diamond, saying its return would be \"a convincing demonstration of the spirit that moved Britain voluntarily to shed its imperial encumbrances and lead the process of decolonisation\". In a letter to the Prime Minister of Pakistan, [[Zulfikar Ali Bhutto]], the Prime Minister of the United Kingdom, [[James Callaghan]], wrote, \"I need not remind you of the various hands through which the stone has passed over the past two centuries, nor that explicit provision for its transfer to the British crown was made in the peace treaty with the Maharajah of Lahore in 1849. I could not advise Her Majesty that it should be surrendered\".<ref>{{cite book|title=Pakistan Horizon|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5H9CAAAAYAAJ|volume=29|year=1976|publisher=Pakistan Institute of International Affairs|page=267}}</ref>\n\n=== Afghanistan ===\nIn 2000, the [[Taliban]]'s foreign affairs spokesman, Faiz Ahmed Faiz, said the Koh-i-Noor was the legitimate property of Afghanistan, and demanded for it to be handed over to the regime. \"The history of the diamond shows it was taken from us (Afghanistan) to India, and from there to Britain. We have a much better claim than the Indians\", he said.<ref name=\"guardian\"/> The Afghan claim derives from Shah Shuja Durrani memoirs, which states he surrendered the diamond to Ranjit Singh while Singh was having his son tortured in front of him, so argue the Maharajah of Lahore acquired the stone illegitimately.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jamal |first1=Momin |title=Kohinoor's story: from treachery to treasury |url=https://dailytimes.com.pk/26635/kohinoors-story-from-treachery-to-treasury/ |accessdate=19 June 2018 |work=Daily Times |date=26 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Possible compromises===\n\nBecause of the quadripartite dispute over the diamond's rightful ownership, there have been various compromises suggested to bring the dispute to an end. These include dividing the diamond into four, with a piece given to each of Afghanistan, India, and Pakistan, with the final piece retained by the [[British Crown]]. Another suggestion is that the jewel be housed in a special museum at the [[Wagah]] border between India and Pakistan. However this suggestion does not cater to Afghan claims, nor the reality of current British possession.{{sfn|Dalrymple|Anand|2017|p=281}} These compromises are presently unaligned with the position of the [[British Government]], which since the end of the [[British Raj]] is that the status of the diamond is 'non-negotiatable'.{{sfn|Dalrymple|Anand|2017|p=272}}\n\n== In popular culture ==\nThe Koh-i-Noor made its first appearance in popular culture in ''[[The Moonstone]]'' (1868), a 19th-century British [[epistolary novel]] by [[Wilkie Collins]], generally considered to be the first full length [[detective novel]] in the English language. In his preface to the first edition of the book, Collins says that he based his eponymous \"Moonstone\" on the histories of two stones: the [[Orlov (diamond)|Orlov]], a {{convert|189.62|carat|g|1|adj=on}} diamond in the Russian Imperial Sceptre, and the Koh-i-Noor.<ref>{{cite book|author=Wilkie Collins|title=The Moonstone: A Novel|url=https://archive.org/details/moonstoneanovel00collgoog|year=1874|publisher=Harper & Brothers|page=[https://archive.org/details/moonstoneanovel00collgoog/page/n14 8]}}</ref> In the 1966 [[Penguin Books]] edition of ''The Moonstone'', [[J. I. M. Stewart]] states that Collins used [[Charles William King|G. C. King]]'s [https://archive.org/details/naturalhistorya00kinggoog ''The Natural History, Ancient and Modern, of Precious Stones \u2026'' (1865)] to research the history of the Koh-i-Noor.<ref>Goodland, p. 136.</ref>\n\nThe Koh-i-Noor also features in [[Agatha Christie]]'s 1925 novel ''[[The Secret of Chimneys]]'' where it is hidden somewhere inside a large country house and is discovered at the end of the novel. The diamond had been stolen from the Tower of London by a Parisian gang leader who replaced it with a replica stone.<ref>{{cite book|last=Bargainnier|first=Earl F.|title=The Gentle Art of Murder: The Detective Fiction of Agatha Christie|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nEAUBOJakoQC&pg=PA89|accessdate=28 August 2018|year=1980|publisher=Popular Press|isbn=978-0-87972-159-6|page=89}}</ref>\n<!-- Please do not make a list of appearances. -->\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Golconda Diamonds]]\n* [[List of diamonds]]\n* [[List of largest rough diamonds]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Noteslist|30em}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|25em}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n{{Refbegin|30em}}\n<!-- A to G -->\n* {{cite book|first=Victor|last=Argenzio|title=Crystal Clear: The Story of Diamonds|url=https://archive.org/details/crystalclearstor00arge|url-access=registration|year=1977|publisher=David McKay Co.|isbn=978-0-679-20317-9}}\n*{{cite book|first=Ian|last=Balfour|title=Famous Diamonds|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ekzrAAAAMAAJ|year=2009|publisher=Antique Collectors' Club|isbn=978-1-85149-479-8}}\n* {{cite book|first1=Hubert|last1=Bari|first2=Violaine|last2=Sautter|title=Diamonds: In the Heart of the Earth, in the Heart of Stars, at the Heart of Power|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oS6pKwAACAAJ|year=2001|publisher=Vilo International|isbn=978-2-84576-032-5}}\n* {{cite book|first=James Andrew|last=Broun-Ramsay|title=Private Letters|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bAzgAAAAMAAJ|edition=2|year=1911|publisher=Blackwood|location=India}}\n* {{cite book|first1=William|last1=Dalrymple|first2=Anita|last2=Anand|title=Koh-i-Noor: The History of the World's Most Infamous Diamond|year=2017|publisher=Bloomsbury|isbn=978-1-408-88886-5|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JFcqDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT95|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|title=The English Regalia|first=Cyril|last=Davenport|year=1897|publisher=K. Paul, Trench, Tr\u00fcbner & Co.|url=https://archive.org/details/englishregalia00daveuoft}}\n* {{cite book|first=John R.|last=Davis|title=The Great Exhibition|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kp8hAQAAIAAJ|year=1999|publisher=Sutton|isbn=978-0-7509-1614-1}}\n* {{cite book|title=The Crown Jewels: Souvenir Guidebook|first1=Sally|last1=Dixon-Smith|first2=Sebastian|last2=Edwards|first3=Sarah|last3=Kilby|first4=Clare|last4=Murphy|first5=David|last5=Souden|first6=Jane|last6=Spooner|first7=Lucy|last7=Worsley|publisher=Historic Royal Palaces|year=2010|isbn=978-1-873993-13-2}}\n* {{cite book|first=Emily|last=Eden|title=Portraits of the Princes and People of India|year=1844|page=14|publisher=J. Dickinson & Son}}\n* {{cite book|first1=Lionel|last1=Fanthorpe|first2=Patricia|last2=Fanthorpe|title=Secrets of the World's Undiscovered Treasures|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=P7zSw4mJmKgC&pg=PA202|year=2009|publisher=Dundurn|isbn=978-1-77070-508-1}}\n* {{cite book|first=Lauren M. E.|last=Goodlad|title=The Victorian Geopolitical Aesthetic: Realism, Sovereignty, and Transnational Experience|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QzQcBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA136|year=2015|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-872827-6}}\n<!-- H to M -->\n* {{cite book|first=Elizabeth|last=Hennessy|title=A Domestic History of the Bank of England, 1930\u20131960|url=https://archive.org/details/domestichistoryo00henn|url-access=registration|page=[https://archive.org/details/domestichistoryo00henn/page/n262 237]|date=1992|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-39140-5}}\n* {{cite book|editor1-first=Karin|editor1-last=Hofmeester|editor2-first=Bernd-Stefan|editor2-last=Grewe|title=Luxury in Global Perspective: Objects and Practices, 1600\u20132000|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eu6SDQAAQBAJ|year=2016|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-1-107-10832-5}}\n* {{cite magazine|first=R. A.|last=Howie|url=http://www.minersoc.org/pages/Archive-MM/Volume_63/63-2-292.pdf|title=Book Reviews|magazine=Mineralogical Magazine|year=1999|volume=63|issue=2|publisher=Mineralogical Society of Great Britain and Ireland}}\n*{{cite journal|first=Nigel B.|last=Israel|title='The Most Unkindest Cut of All' - Recutting the Koh-i-Nur|journal=Journal of Gemmology|year=1992|volume=23|number=3|page=176|issn=0022-1252|doi=10.15506/JoG.1992.23.3.176}}\n* {{cite book|first=Anna|last=Keay|title=The Crown Jewels|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MwpjtwAACAAJ|year=2011|publisher=Thames & Hudson|isbn=978-0-500-51575-4}}\n* {{cite book|first=T. K.|last=Kurien|title=Geology and Mineral Resources of Andhra Pradesh|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=r20IAAAAIAAJ|year=1980|publisher=Geological Survey of India}}\n* {{cite book|first=Jean Marie|last=Lafont|title=Maharaja Ranjit Singh: Lord of the Five Rivers|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zjduAAAAMAAJ|year=2002|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-566111-8}}\n* {{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/sirjohnloginand00logigoog|title=Sir John Login and Duleep Singh|first=Lena Campbell|last=[[Lena Login|Login]]|year=1890|publisher=Languages Dept|location=Punjab}} \n* {{cite book|first=Kenneth J.|last=Mears|title=The Tower of London: 900 Years of English History|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=D_kgAAAAMAAJ|year=1988|publisher=Phaidon|isbn=978-0-7148-2527-4}}\n* {{cite book|first1=Kenneth J.|last1=Mears|first2=Simon|last2=Thurley|first3=Claire|last3=Murphy|title=The Crown Jewels|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=r1GJnAEACAAJ|year=1994|publisher=Historic Royal Palaces|asin=B000HHY1ZQ}}\n<!-- R to Y -->\n* {{cite book|first=P. N.|last=Rastogi|title=Ethnic Tensions in Indian Society: Explanation, Prediction, Monitoring and Control|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xBOlsFQH-toC|year=1986|publisher=Mittal Publications|isbn=978-9-997-38489-8}}\n* {{cite book|first=Tessa|last=Rose|title=The Coronation Ceremony and the Crown Jewels|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bSUTAQAAIAAJ|year=1992|publisher=HM Stationery Office|isbn=978-0-117-01361-2}}\n* {{cite book|first=Henry George|last=Smith|title=Gems and Precious Stones|url=https://archive.org/details/gemspreciousston00smitrich|year=1896|publisher=Charles Potter}}\n* {{cite book|first1=Edwin William|last1=Streeter|first2=Joseph|last2=Hatten|title=The Great Diamonds of the World|url=https://archive.org/details/greatdiamondsofw00stre|year=1882|publisher=G. Bell & Sons}}\n* {{cite journal|last1=Sucher|first1=Scott D.|last2=Carriere|first2=Dale P.|year=2008|title=The Use of Laser and X-ray Scanning to Create a Model of the Historic Koh-i-Noor Diamond|journal=Gems & Gemology|volume=44|issue=2|pages=124\u2013141|doi=10.5741/GEMS.44.2.124}}\n* {{cite journal|journal=New Zealand Journal of History|volume=15|issue=1|issn=0028-8322|date=April 1981|first=Nicholas|last=Tarling|authorlink=Nicholas Tarling|publisher=University of Auckland|url=http://www.nzjh.auckland.ac.nz/docs/1981/NZJH_15_1_03.pdf|title=The Wars of British Succession}}\n* {{cite journal |first=Dena K.|last=Tarshis |year=2000 |title=The Koh-i-Noor Diamond and its Glass Replica at the Crystal Palace Exhibition |jstor=24191006 |journal=Journal of Glass Studies |publisher=Corning Museum of Glass |volume=42 |pages=133\u2013143 |issn=0075-4250 }}\n* {{cite journal |last=Young |first=Paul |year=2007 |title=\"Carbon, Mere Carbon\": The Kohinoor, the Crystal Palace, and the Mission to Make Sense of British India |url= |journal=Nineteenth-Century Contexts |volume=29 |issue=4 |pages=343\u2013358 |doi=10.1080/08905490701768089 }}\n* {{cite book|first1=Sir George|last1=Younghusband|first2=Cyril|last2=Davenport|title=The Crown Jewels of England|url=https://archive.org/details/TheCrownJewelsOfEngland|year=1919|publisher=Cassell & Co.|asin=B00086FM86}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Koh-i-Noor Diamond}}\n* {{Wikisource-inline|links=[[s:The Folk-Lore Journal/Volume 4/A Story of the Koh-i-N\u00fbr|the Koh-i-Noor]]}}\n\n{{Crown Jewels of the United Kingdom}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Koh-I-Noor}}\n[[Category:Crown Jewels of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Jewels of the Mughal Empire]]\n[[Category:Diamonds originating in India]]\n[[Category:History of India]]\n[[Category:History of Andhra Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Sikh Empire]]\n[[Category:1739 in Asia]]\n[[Category:Persian words and phrases]]\n[[Category:Golconda diamonds]]\n", "name_user": "Firebrace", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:MOS:OVERLINK.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Koh-i-Noor"}
{"title_page": "In Your Eyes (The Weeknd song)", "text_new": "{{short description|2020 single by The Weeknd}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name          = In Your Eyes\n| cover         =\n| type          = single\n| artist        = [[The Weeknd]]\n| album           = [[After Hours (The Weeknd album)|After Hours]]\n| released      = {{Start date|2020|03|24|mf=yes}}\n| format        = {{hlist|[[Music download|Digital download]]|[[Streaming media|streaming]]}}\n| recorded      =\n| studio        = \n* [[Conway Recording Studios|Conway]], [[Maratone Studios|MXM]] (Los Angeles, California)\n* House Mouse Studios, MXM (Stockholm, Sweden)\n| genre         = \n* [[Synth-pop]]<ref name=\"La Canci\u00f3n Del D\u00eda\"/>\n* [[post-disco]]<ref name=\"La Canci\u00f3n Del D\u00eda\"/>\n| length        = 3:57\n| label         = \n* [[XO (record label)|XO]]\n* [[Republic Records|Republic]]\n| writer        = \n* [[The Weeknd|Abel Tesfaye]]\n* [[Belly (rapper)|Ahmad Balshe]]\n* [[Max Martin]]\n* [[Oscar Holter]]\n| producer      = {{hlist|Max Martin|Oscar Holter|The Weeknd}}\n| chronology    = [[The Weeknd]]\n| prev_title    = [[Blinding Lights]]\n| prev_year     = 2019\n| next_title    = \n| next_year     = \n| misc          = {{External music video|{{YouTube|dqRZDebPIGs|In Your Eyes\"}}}}\n}}\n\"'''In Your Eyes'''\" is a song by Canadian singer [[The Weeknd]] from his fourth studio album ''[[After Hours (The Weeknd album)|After Hours]]'' (2020).<ref>{{cite tweet|user=gthot20|number=1240851448952487936|title=@theweeknd \"In Your Eyes\" goes to pop radio next week...|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref> The song was serviced to [[contemporary hit radio]] on March 24, 2020 by [[XO (record label)|XO]] and [[Republic Records]] as the album's third single. It was originally released four days before, alongside the rest of its parent album.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rap-up.com/2020/03/17/the-weeknd-after-hours-tracklist/|title=The Weeknd Reveals 'After Hours' Tracklist|website=Rap-Up|accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref> The Weeknd wrote and produced the song with [[Max Martin]] and [[Oscar Holter]], with Canadian rapper [[Belly (rapper)|Belly]] receiving additional writing credits as well.<ref name=\"Tidal\"/>\n\n==Background and release==\nThe song was first teased in The Weeknd's ''After Hours'' short film (released early March 2020) during a scene in which Tesfaye walked passed a musician playing the track's saxophone solo.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/music/news/the-weeknd-after-hours-short-film-watch-video-1203524075/|title=Watch The Weeknd\u2019s Disturbing Short Film for \u2018After Hours\u2019|first1=Jem|last1=Aswad|first2=Jem|last2=Aswad|date=March 4, 2020|accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref> Later on, [[Island Records]] president Louis Bloom, in a mid-March 2020 interview with ''[[Music Week]]'' magazine, confirmed that a direct follow-up to \"[[Blinding Lights]]\" was set to be revealed upon the album's release.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/the-weeknds-label-boss-teases-big-follow-up-song-to-his-uk-number-1-blinding-lights-on-new-album-after-hours__29094/|title=The Weeknd's label boss teases big follow up to Blinding Lights|website=www.officialcharts.com|accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref> The follow-up was then annouced to be \"In Your Eyes\", with the song being added to various popular [[Spotify]] playlists and having its radio release confirmed by Gary Trust of ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' magazine on March 20, 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://open.spotify.com/playlist/37i9dQZF1DXcBWIGoYBM5M?si=yaY3bgEITAGYEhNhaEuWUg&_php=1|title=Today's Top Hits on Spotify (March 20, 2020)|date=March 20, 2020|website=Spotify|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320060128/https://open.spotify.com/playlist/37i9dQZF1DXcBWIGoYBM5M?si=yaY3bgEITAGYEhNhaEuWUg&_php=1|archive-date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Lyrics==\nThe lyrics of the song reference Tesfaye's on-and-off relationship with model [[Bella Hadid]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usmagazine.com/entertainment/news/twitter-thinks-the-weeknd-album-after-hours-is-about-bella-hadid/|title=Twitter Is Convinced The Weeknd\u2019s \u2018Entire\u2019 New Album Is About Bella Hadid|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hollywoodlife.com/2020/03/20/the-weeknd-after-hours-album-bella-hadid-songs/|title=The Weeknd\u2019s Fans Are Convinced That He Drops Multiple References To Bella Hadid In New Album|first=Jason Brow,Jade|last=Boren|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref> In the track, The Weeknd sings about feeling remorse over being unfaithful in the relationship that he had with his partner.<ref name=\"La Canci\u00f3n Del D\u00eda\"/> The song's lyrics serves as a contrast to the high energy and hopefulness found in the album's previous track \"[[Blinding Lights]]\", with the single taking on a more melancholic tone in its writing.<ref name=\"La Canci\u00f3n Del D\u00eda\"/> \n\n==Critical reception==\nThe song was noted as a standout track from the album by critics, with the single being compared to The Weeknd's previous radio hits.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/the-weeknd-looks-into-the-windows-of-the-soul-on-in-your-eyes-new-song.1986605.html|title=The Weeknd Looks Into The Windows Of The Soul On \"In Your Eyes\"|website=HotNewHipHop|accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.breakingnews.fr/divertissement/the-weeknd-regarde-dans-les-fenetres-de-lame-sur-in-your-eyes-370470.html|title=The Weeknd regarde dans les fen\u00eatres de l'\u00e2me sur \"In Your Eyes\"|first=Breaking|last=News|date=March 20, 2020|website=Vivez l'actualit\u00e9 avec Breakingnews.fr|accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref> Various journalists noted its heavy 80s influence, with the song's saxophone solo (performed by Wojtek Goral) and synths receiving praise and being compared to hits such as [[M83 (band)|M83]]'s \"[[Midnight City]]\" and [[Katy Perry]]'s \"[[Last Friday Night]]\".<ref name=\"La Canci\u00f3n Del D\u00eda\">{{Cite web|url=https://jenesaispop.com/2020/03/20/386848/la-cancion-del-dia-in-your-eyes-es-otra-gran-cancion-del-the-weeknd-mas-pop/|title=La Canci\u00f3n Del D\u00eda: 'In Your Eyes' es otra canci\u00f3n incontestable del The Weeknd m\u00e1s pop|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thefader.com/2020/03/20/7-albums-to-stream-weeknd-jbalvin-sada-baby|title=The 7 new albums you should stream right now|website=The FADER|accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://djbooth.net/features/2020-03-20-the-weeknd-after-hours-album-review-new-music|title=The Weeknd \u2018After Hours\u2019 Album Review|first=Yoh|last=Phillips|website=DJBooth}}</ref>\n\n==Music video==\nThe music video for \"In Your Eyes\" was first teased by its director Anton Tammi on his [[Instagram]] story on March 21, 2020, with Tesfaye later on the following day posting the thumbnail for the visual on his social media accounts.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/screenshot20200321220414|title=Screenshots of Anton Tammi's Instagram Story on March 21, 2020|publisher=Instagram|accessdate=March 23, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet|user=TheWeeknd|number=1241768186359328769|title=saga continues tomorrow - The Weeknd|date=March 22, 2020|accessdate=March 23, 2020}}</ref> Its confirmation as the music video for the single was confirmed eleven hours before its release, with the video premiering on March 23, 2020.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=TheWeeknd|number=1241950188060606464|title=tune in, in the morning - The Weeknd|date=March 23, 2020|accessdate=March 23, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thefader.com/2020/03/23/the-weeknd-in-your-eyes-video|title=The Weeknd shares \u201cIn Your Eyes\u201d video|website=The Fader|accessdate=March 23, 2020}}</ref> The visual stars Zaina Miuccia as the lead female protagonist and continues the storyline from the ''[[After Hours (The Weeknd album)#Release and promotion|After Hours]]'' short film after The Weeknd enters the elevator with the couple.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/the-weeknd-loses-his-head-in-gory-new-in-your-eyes-video/|title=The Weeknd Loses His Head in Gory New \"In Your Eyes\" Video|website=Pitchfork|accessdate=March 23, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B-C3mwpprka/|title=Anton Tammi on Instagram: \"saga continues tomorrow. starring: Zaina Miuccia @theweeknd\"|website=Instagram|accessdate=March 23, 2020}}</ref> In the music video, The Weeknd, after having killed Miuccia's companion in the aforementioned elevator, chases her throughout different locations until they reach a nightclub named After Hours. There, Miuccia manages to grab an axe that she then uses to decapitate the Weeknd, with her then proceeding to dance with his lifeless head throughout the rest of the music video.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2020/03/the-weeknd-in-your-eyes-video|title=The Weeknd Shares Blood-Soaked \"In Your Eyes\" Video|website=Complex|accessdate=March 23, 2020}}</ref> The visual features the return of Wojtek Goral as the saxophone player from the album's self-titled short film and was compared to the slasher movies of the 1980s, being met with a positive reception.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stereogum.com/2077699/the-weeknds-in-your-eyes-video-is-an-amazing-slasher-movie-parody/video/|title=The Weeknd's \"In Your Eyes\" Video Is An Amazing Slasher-Movie Parody: Watch|date=March 23, 2020|accessdate=March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Commercial performance==\nFollowing the releasing of its parent album, \"In Your Eyes\" debuted at number 16 on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] dated April 4, 2020. It was the highest overall debut of the week and third highest charting track from ''After Hours''.<ref name=\"Hot 100 Peak\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/amp/articles/business/chart-beat/9346588/every-song-weeknd-after-hours-hot-100|title=Every Song From The Weeknd's 'After Hours' Is on the Hot 100|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|last=Zellener|first=Xander|date=March 30, 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe song debuted at number 17 on the [[UK Singles Chart]], becoming his 20th top 40 hit on the chart.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/artist/22895/weeknd/|title=The Weeknd {{!}} full Official Chart History {{!}} Official Charts Company|website=www.officialcharts.com|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> Elsewhere in Europe, it managed to debut in the top 20 of the Belgian Tip charts, Irish Singles Chart, and Dutch Single Top 100. The song also managed to debut within the top ten of Norwegian and Swedish charts, with the single also reaching a top 40 position of number 26 in Italy.<!-- See charts section. -->\n\n==Personnel==\nCredits adapted from [[Tidal (service)|Tidal]].<ref name=\"Tidal\">{{cite web|url=https://listen.tidal.com/album/134815153|title=After Hours / The Weeknd \u2013 Tidal|website=[[Tidal (service)|Tidal]]|accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref> \n* [[The Weeknd]] \u2013 vocals, songwriting, production\n* [[Belly (rapper)|Belly]] \u2013 songwriting\n* [[Max Martin]] \u2013 songwriting, production\n* [[Oscar Holter]] \u2013 songwriting, production\n* Dave Kutch \u2013 mastering \n* Kevin Peterson \u2013 mastering\n\n==Charts==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2020)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{single chart|Australia|13|artist=The Weeknd|song=In Your Eyes|rowheader=true|accessdate=March 28, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Austria|23|artist=The Weeknd|rowheader=true|song=In Your Eyes|accessdate=April 2, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Flanders|41|artist=The Weeknd|song=In Your Eyes|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 10, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Wallonia Tip|2|artist=The Weeknd|song=In Your Eyes|rowheader=true|accessdate=Ap